<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Folger Library Features Shakespeare  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Shelved among some of the world's finest and
rarest books in the vaults of the Folger Shakespeare Library, one
scuffed and waterstained volume stands out, not for its pedigree
but for the life it has led.
</P>
<P>
   The faded flyleaf inscription on an otherwise quite ordinary
copy of the comedies of William Shakespeare tells the story: ''This
volume left for California March 15, 1849 via the way of the plains
and arrived home, the 17th of May, 1857.''
</P>
<P>
   Gold was discovered in California in 1848. The next year, scores
of thousands of Americans followed the golden lure west. The book's
owner (she signed herself ''Boneta,'' but her full identity is
unknown) chose Shakespeare's comedies as a companion on the
difficult trek across the continent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look at the water stains,'' says Georgianna Ziegler, reference
librarian at the Folger. ''This book has obviously been through
things. It's part of the story of the way west. I think it's a
great piece of Americana.''
</P>
<P>
   The book, published in Hartford, Conn., in 1834, is also a
symbol of the world's attachment to the plays and poetry of a 16th
century English writer whose work has caught the imagination of
every era and circumstance, no matter how unlike his own.
</P>
<P>
   Situated just a glance away from the House and Senate, the
Folger library is one place on Capitol Hill that ignores politics
and the dance of legislation. It lays claim instead to the ''most
brisk and giddy-paced times'' of Shakespeare's England.
</P>
<P>
   Among its 250,000 books the Folger shelters the world's largest
collection of Shakespeare First Folios, 79 of the 240 known to
exist. It holds 150,000 English and European books printed between
1475 and 1800, including volumes on law and economics and social
and political history. It highlights theatrical history with
drawings, paintings, promptbooks and playbills of Shakespearian
productions over four centuries.
</P>
<P>
   The library attracts some 200,000 visitors a year to its dark
wood Elizabethan exhibit hall and to dramatic and musical
performances in its Elizabethan theater. About 1,000 scholars use
its resources each year.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1991 visit, Queen Elizabeth II came face to face at the
Folger with a portrait of her distant cousin, Elizabeth I, the
British monarch of Shakespeare's times.
</P>
<P>
   To get some idea of the breadth of the Folger's holdings, just
pull one thread in a large, complex and multicolored tapestry, in
this case Shakespeare's link to America.
</P>
<P>
   Ziegler reaches into a gray-metal cart and places a small red
volume on the table next to the Shakespeare that went west with the
Forty Niners. The inscription from President Franklin D. Roosevelt
reads: ''... given by me to my mother Sara Delano Roosevelt around
1900 and was in her room at Hyde Park until her death in 1941 when
it came back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Next is an 1864 Shakespeare published in Cincinnati and
presented in 1865 at the end of the Civil War to Clara Barton, the
future founder of the American Red Cross, for ''services rendered
to the sick and wounded at the Flying Hospital 10th Army Corps in
front of Richmond.''
</P>
<P>
   There is an 1825 Shakespeare owned by Oliver Wendell Holmes Sr.,
one of the best-loved American poets of the 19th century. It was
given to the library in 1931 by his son, Supreme Court Justice
Oliver Wendell Holmes Jr., who said he remembered it from his
boyhood.
</P>
<P>
   There is a leather-bound promptbook from a London production of
Othello that belonged to actor Paul Robeson, who played the title
role but as a black man was barred by America's color line from
playing opposite a white actress in a U.S. theater.
</P>
<P>
   The library owes its existence to a chain of events that began
to form when the aging Ralph Waldo Emerson lectured at Amherst
College in 1879 and stirred the interest of a student named Henry
Clay Folger.
</P>
<P>
   Folger, who was to become president and chairman of the Standard
Oil Co., paid 25 cents for a ticket to hear Emerson speak. What the
philosopher had to say about Shakespeare caught fire in the
student's mind.
</P>
<P>
   Years earlier, Emerson, summing up the influence of Shakespeare
on the 300th anniversary of his birth, wrote a sentence that Folger
was to take to heart:
</P>
<P>
   ''Genius is the consoler of our mortal condition, and
Shakespeare taught us that the little world of the heart is vaster,
deeper and richer than the spaces of astronomy.''
</P>
<P>
   Folger's passionate study of Shakespeare and determination to
create the definitive collection of the bard's works grew parallel
to his business success. He died in 1930, soon after the
cornerstone was laid for the building he had envisioned as a
permanent home for his collections and as a major center for the
study of Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   The vision has been maintained.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lawrence L. Knutson has covered the White House,
Congress and Washington's history for more than 30 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
