<HEADLINE> Some Conservatives Eye Lieberman  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID HO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Recent criticism of Joseph Lieberman's
expressions of faith has placed religious conservatives in the odd
role of defending the Democratic vice presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist William Bennett said Sunday there is a
national tradition of politicians speaking about religion and there
is worse discourse in popular entertainment and media.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our kids are not really being overcome by piety,'' Bennett
said on CBS' ''Face the Nation. ''This is not the major problem in
American life.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian Coalition founder Pat Robertson said he found the
statements by Lieberman refreshing after President Clinton's
personal trials. Since becoming Vice President Al Gore's running
mate, Lieberman, who is Jewish, has often talked about religion.
</P>
<P>
   ''He feels this deeply and that's why the religious
conservatives like him a lot and they like Orthodox Jews,''
Robertson said on ABC's ''This Week.'' ''They like people who will
stand up for their faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Television evangelist Jerry Falwell also sided with Lieberman,
saying on CNN's ''Late Edition:'' ''To limit someone's expression
of free speech on any subject, including religion, is a violation
of the First Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   In talking about faith, Lieberman has used language more
identified with conservative evangelicals, including his contention
that the Constitution does not demand ''freedom from religion,''
but only freedom ''of'' religion. He recently celebrated
accomplishments of the Clinton-Gore administration by comparing
them to the parting of the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk drew criticism last week from the Anti-Defamation
League, which warned Lieberman that his repeated expressions of
religion risked alienating some voters.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman defended himself Sunday in a conference call with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''My own expressions of last week were really meant to be
inclusive and tolerant, including tolerant of that minority of the
American public that does not believe in God,'' he said before
joining Gore on a 24-hour Labor Day campaign sprint through five
states.
</P>
<P>
   While conservatives may respect Lieberman, they saw a political
calculation in the background.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett alleged that Democrats were taking advantage of
Lieberman's tendency to speak about religion.
</P>
<P>
   ''As natural as that is to him, I think the political
calculation is the most natural thing to the Gore campaign. I'm
sure they're seeing how this is playing and they're saying, 'Stay
at it, Joe,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson worried that Lieberman's sincerity could attract
members of the religious right and former Democrats had who drifted
away from the party.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a Republican, I'm not particularly pleased because he's
gaining a lot of votes for Al Gore,'' Robertson said. ''This is a
brilliant strategic move and the Democrats are chortling
enormously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 0059 </TRAILER>
