<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Ticket Starting Campaign Tour  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- A parade in suburban Chicago and a stop at a
Michigan peach festival led George W. Bush's Labor Day itinerary as
he kicks off his fall presidential campaign with a weeklong tour
through states where the race is wide open.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican nominee plans to visit nine cities in Illinois,
Michigan, Pennsylvania, Wisconsin, Indiana and Ohio, states that
represent 107 electoral votes, or about 40 percent of the 270
needed for victory in November.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton handily won each state except Indiana in 1996,
but four years later they are considered toss-ups. Polls show Bush
and Vice President Al Gore in a dead heat in most of the states,
where millions of independent voters who tend to swing between the
two major parties will probably decide the election.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's schedule Monday put him in two major media markets --
Chicago and Detroit. He and running mate Dick Cheney were taking
part first in a parade in Naperville, Ill., a GOP-friendly suburb
of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The two were to split up later in the day, with Bush flying to
Romeo, Mich., north of Detroit, for the state's annual peach
festival and Cheney attending a Polish food fair in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will focus on Medicare, the economy, taxes, defense
readiness and Social Security during the multistate tour, his
campaign said. He is expected to announce a proposal for providing
prescription coverage for seniors on Tuesday in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush's Democratic rival, Vice President Al Gore, and
running mate Joseph Lieberman were campaigning around the clock on
Monday, visiting five battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day is a symbolically important landmark in the election
season. Political observers believe many Americans who have not
paid much attention to the presidential race over the summer start
tuning in after the holiday, so the parties switch into high gear,
running more ads and putting candidates on the road full time.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee began airing an ad over the
weekend that features Gore's 1996 visit to a Buddhist temple and
his 1999 claim to have created the Internet. Both parties are
running ads touting dueling approaches for providing prescription
drug coverage for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates are also jousting over debates. On Sunday, Bush
said he had accepted three invitations to debate Gore on prime-time
television, including one on Sept. 12 during a special edition of
NBC's ''Meet the Press'' and two in October.
</P>
<P>
   Gore wouldn't agree to the schedule, saying it could limit the
audience and the amount of face-to-face debate time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 0100 </TRAILER>
