<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Concord Inquiry Focuses on Metal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Continental Airlines said it is working with
French authorities to determine if a 17-inch strip of metal found
on a runway after July's fatal Concorde's crash is from a
Continental DC-10.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have said the piece of metal may have gashed a tire
on the Air France Concorde, triggering the chain of events that
brought the supersonic aircraft down in flames in the town of
Gonesse, killing 113 on July 25.
</P>
<P>
   An inspection Saturday by Continental, the Federal Aviation
Administration, the National Transportation Safety Board and French
officials revealed that a strip similar to the one found on the
runway was missing from a space between a fan and a door on the
right-wing engine of a Continental DC-10.
</P>
<P>
   According to Continental, the same DC-10 was operating the day
of the crash between Charles de Gaulle Airport, where the ill-fated
Concorde took off, and Newark International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   However, investigators said they were unable to conclusively
determine if the metal piece -- called a wear strip -- was the same
piece that was missing from the Continental aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone call placed to Continental late Sunday by The
Associated Press was not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
