<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mom, 2 young children killed in apartment  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) - A 28-year-old woman and two of her young
children were killed in their apartment while music blared Sunday
morning, The Journal News reported.
</P>
<P>
   A third child, a 9-year-old boy, was hospitalized but was
expected to live, Westchester County District Attorney Jeanine
Pirro said. A 23-year-old man, possibly the woman's boyfriend, also
was hospitalized with apparent stab wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro declined to provide details on what police found at the
first-floor apartment at 55 Maple St. in the Nodine Hill section.
Yonkers police released no information.
</P>
<P>
   The dead, identified as Patricia Torres, 28, Ashley Dominguez,
4, and William Santiago, 7, were found shortly before 8 a.m.
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-year-old boy was in critical condition at Jacobi Medical
Center in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ''As you can imagine, a homicide scene with a mother and two
children is very disturbing,'' said Pirro, the district attorney.
''We are doing everything we can to make sure the case we put
together, if it is prosecuted, is a solid one.''
</P>
<P>
   Iklass Ibrahim, the landlord and owner of 55 and 57 Maple St.
for the last six years, said that the 23-year-old man is Torres'
boyfriend and that the two had a stormy relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was a nice tenant, but she had a lot of problems with
him,'' Ibrahim said.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim said that the couple lived together with the children
and that she had received many complaints from tenants saying
Torres and her boyfriend were fighting or playing music loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Some neighbors said they heard loud music at the apartment
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Angelo Squillante, 56, who lives down the block, said he heard
screams from the yard at 7 a.m. Sunday. He said the victims were
discovered by another of Torres' children, an 11-year-old boy who
lives with Torres' parents at 53 Maple St.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw them bring him out through the front on a stretcher,''
Squillante said, referring to 7-year-old William.
</P>
<P>
   The dead woman's parents, Rodolfo Torres, 65, and Sergia Torres,
61, sat somberly at their kitchen table Sunday. Rodolfo Torres
occasionally ventured outside his home to smoke a cigarette and
silently pace the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're in too much pain to speak,'' said Norman Doblado, 32,
the dead woman's cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Hector Ortiz said Patricia Torres' boys used to come
over to play video games with his children.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes they come here, when I make a party for my kids,''
he told The Journal News. ''They're nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after dark Sunday, at least a dozen children played on the
sidewalk outside the building. Two police officers guarded the
entrance to the crime scene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
