<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, Japan Discuss Treaty  </HEADLINE>
By CHISAKI WATANABE
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin and Japanese Prime
Minister Yoshiro Mori opened talks on Monday on a World War II
peace treaty delayed by a territorial dispute over four islands
north of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Soviet troops occupied the four Kuril Islands, known in Japan as
the Northern Territories, during the closing days of the war. Tokyo
has insisted on a deal on the islands as a condition for concluding
a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope our talks will develop in a good direction,'' Mori was
quoted by Kyodo News agency as telling Putin at the outset of talks
at the State Guesthouse in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and Russia are trying to wrap up a peace treaty by the end
of this year. Tokyo and Moscow established diplomatic relations in
1956, but have never signed a treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are still far apart. Tokyo is demanding
recognition of its territorial claims. But before he left Russia,
Putin told the Interfax news agency that he would not bargain the
islands away.
</P>
<P>
   In a 90-minute session Monday morning, Mori reiterated Tokyo's
1998 proposal of continued Russian administration of the territory
in exchange for recognition of Japanese claims on the islands, the
Japanese Foreign Ministry said. Moscow has not accepted that
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Mori also repeated the goal of concluding a treaty this year, a
ministry official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, however, was quoted as saying that while the Tokyo
proposal did not match Moscow's thinking on the issue, his
government was committed to continued talks.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders were to meet again in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Another top discussion item in the two-day talks is economic
ties. Russian and Japanese officials plan to sign a dozen
agreements, including a program on developing trade and economic
relations and a separate document on joint efforts to aid the
economic development of the Kurils.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Putin and Mori are expected to sign agreements on
cooperation in energy, Japanese assistance in dismantling Russian
nuclear arsenals and strengthening cooperation between the two
nations' border guards.
</P>
<P>
   Putin arrived in Japan on Sunday. Monday's meeting was Putin's
third with Mori this year and his second visit to Japan as
president. He attended the Group of Eight summit of world leaders
in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 0149 </TRAILER>
