<HEADLINE> World Cup Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN WADE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jamaica, Mexico, and Trinidad and Tobago clinched three of the
six spots in next year's final round of North and Central American
and Caribbean qualifying for the 2002 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Cuauhtemoc Blanco scored twice as Mexico routed visiting Panama
7-1, and Trinidad and Tobago beat visiting Canada 4-0, clinching
both of the spots in Group C.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica beat visiting St. Vincent and the Grenadines 2-0 to
ensure itself one of the two spots in Group D, leaving Honduras and
El Salvador fighting for the other berth.
</P>
<P>
   In Group E, where not berths are assured, the United States took
pressure off itself with a 1-0 win over Guatemala on Brian
McBride's 72nd-minute goal. Costa Rica beat visiting Barbados 3-0
in the other Group E game.
</P>
<P>
   As the first big weekend of European qualifying ended, Ferenc
Horvath scored his second goal of the game in the 79th minute as
Hungary rallied to tie Italy 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Filippo Inzaghi scored for Italy in the 26th and 35th minutes,
and Horvath got his first in the 29th in the Group Eight match. It
was Italy's first game since losing the European Championship final
to France.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's other European qualifiers, it was the Faeroe Islands
2, Slovenia 2; Yugoslavia 2, Luxembourg 0; Portugal 3, Estonia 1;
Slovakia 2, Macedonia 0; Israel 2, Liechtenstein 0; and Romania 1,
Lithuania 0.
</P>
<P>
   In South America, it was Brazil 5, Bolivia 0; Argentina 2, Peru
1; and Uruguay 4, Ecuador 0.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina (6-1-1) leads with 19 points, followed by Colombia
(4-1-3) with 15. Uruguay, Brazil and Paraguay (each 4-2-2) have 14
apiece, while Chile and Ecuador (each 3-4-1) have 10 apiece. Peru
(2-4-2) has eight, followed by Bolivia (1-5-2) with five and
Venezuela (1-7) with three.
</P>
<P>
   The top four teams in South America qualify for the World Cup,
and the fifth-place team goes into a playoff with the Oceania
champion.
</P>
<P>
North and Central America and Caribbean
Group E
United States 1, Guatemala 0
</P>
<P>
   At Washington, McBride scored off a perfect cross from Cobi
Jones in the 72nd minute as the United States, playing a man short,
escaped.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans, desperately needing a win to avoid putting
themselves in must-win situations for their final two games, were
rocked in the 65th minute. Eddie Lewis, who had entered seven
minutes earlier, was ejected by Mexican referee Ulises Rangel for
elbowing Fabricio Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rica (3-1), which plays the U.S. team on Oct. 11 at
Columbus, Ohio, leads the group with nine points, followed the
United States with seven, Guatemala (1-2-1) with four and Barbados
(1-3) with three.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica 3, Barbados 0
</P>
<P>
   At San Jose, Jafet Soto scored in the 35th minute. Rolando
Fonseca connected in the 40th and Hernan Medford converted a
penalty kick in the 53rd.
</P>
<P>
Group C
Trinidad and Tobago 4, Canada 0
</P>
<P>
   At Port-of-Spain, Russell Latapy (28th), Reynold Carrington
(30th), Stokely Mason (52nd) and Angus Eve (87th) scored to
eliminate Canada, which hasn't made the World Cup since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Trinidad and Tobago (4-0) leads the group with 12 points,
followed by Mexico (3-1) with nine, and Canada and Panama (each
0-3-1) with one apiece.
</P>
<P>
Mexico 7, Panama 1
</P>
<P>
   At Mexico City, Victor Ruiz scored in the sixth minute; Manuel
Abundis in the 35th and Miguel Zepeda in the 43rd as Mexico took a
3-0 lead at the half. Blanco scored in the 47th and 90th minutes,
Rafael Marquez in the 53rd and Ramon Ramirez in the 69th. Jorge
Dely Valdez scored for Panama in the 48th.
</P>
<P>
Group D
Jamaica 2, St. Vincent and the Grenadines 0
</P>
<P>
   At Kingston, Jamaica, Andy Williams (44th) and Onandi Lowe
(50th) scored for Jamaica, coming off its first World Cup
appearance in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaica (4-0) has 12 points, followed by Honduras (3-1) with
seven, El Salvador (1-3) with three and St. Vincent (0-4) with
none.
</P>
<P>
Europe
Group One
Faeroe Islands 2, Slovenia 2
</P>
<P>
   At Torshavn, Faeroe Islands, the Atlantic islanders tied
Slovenia with Oessur Hansen scoring the equalizer in injury time.
Uni Arge also scored for the Faeroe Islands. Saso Udovic and Milan
Osterc scored for Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia 2, Luxembourg 0
</P>
<P>
   At Luxembourg, Savo Milosevic and Slavisa Jokanovic scored for
Yugoslavia, under new coach Ilija Petkovic.
</P>
<P>
Group Two
Portugal 3, Estonia 1
</P>
<P>
   At Tallinn, Estonia, Manuel Rui Costa, Luis Figo and Ricardo Sa
Pinto scored in the first 54 minutes for Portugal, and Andres Oper
scored in the 84th for Estonia.
</P>
<P>
Group Four
Slovakia 2, Macedonia 0
</P>
<P>
   At Bratislava, Slovakia, Igor Balis scored in the third minute
and Igor Demo added the second in the 74th.
</P>
<P>
Group Seven
Israel 2, Leichtenstein 0
</P>
<P>
   At Ramat Gan, Israel, Alon Mizrahi scored after just 16 seconds
and Pini Balili got the other in the 79th.
</P>
<P>
Group Eight
Romania 1, Lithuania 0
</P>
<P>
   At Bucharest, Romania, Ioan Ganea scored in the 89th minute.
</P>
<P>
South America
Brazil 5, Bolivia 0
</P>
<P>
   At Rio de Janeiro, Romario scored three times in his first game
for Brazil since 1998, converting a penalty kick in the 11th minute
and adding goals in the 78th and 80th minutes. Rivaldo (46th), who
leads South American scorers with five goals, and Marques (88th)
also connected.
</P>
<P>
Argentina 2, Peru 1
</P>
<P>
   At Lima, Peru, Hernan Crespo (25th) and Juan Sebastian Veron
(37th) scored as Argentina won without injured star forward Gabriel
Batistuta.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay 4, Ecuador 0
</P>
<P>
   At Montevideo, Uruguay, Federico Magallanes (15th), Dario Silva
(38th), Nicolas Oliviera (46th) and Gabriek Cedras (87th) scored.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
