<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops Attack Rebels  </HEADLINE>
By DILIP GANGULY
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Government troops launched a massive
attack on Tamil rebels in the northern Jaffna Peninsula, killing at
least 230 combatants on both sides, military officials and rebels
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Government troops advanced on five fronts on the peninsula
Sunday, but faced tough resistance from the separatist guerrillas
during the 12-hour battle, said the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam. The group is fighting for a Tamil homeland in Sri Lanka, an
island country in the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Eight army officers and 63 government soldiers were killed and
479 soldiers were wounded, military spokesman Sanath Karunaratne
said.
</P>
<P>
   Tamil rebels claimed more than 100 government soldiers were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels did not mention their own casualties, but Karunaratne
claimed about 160 rebels were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The military launched the offensive to boost its defense of
Jaffna, the former rebel capital that has come under government
control. The guerrillas have been trying to recapture Jaffna since
April.
</P>
<P>
   ''Facing superior fire power from land and from air, the LTTE
combat formations are putting up fierce resistance inflicting heavy
casualties on the government troops,'' the rebel statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed thrust by government troops broke a four-month lull
in fighting on the peninsula. The rebels fired mortars Wednesday at
government defenses in Meesalai, 12 miles east of Jaffna city.
</P>
<P>
   No independent confirmation is possible, as journalists are not
permitted in the war zone. Media censorship was imposed in May
after the military lost several battles to the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The Tamil rebels seek an independent homeland in the country's
north and east, claiming widespread discrimination in education and
jobs by the majority Sinhalese. The government denies the charge.
</P>
<P>
   More than 62,000 people have died during the 17-year war.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Tamil Rebel Web site: http://www.eelamweb.com
</P>
<P>
   Government Web site: http://www.priu.gov.lk
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
