<HEADLINE> Sylvan Beach reopens, Verona Beach still closed after spill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYLVAN BEACH, N.Y. (AP) - A swimming ban at Sylvan Beach has
been lifted, but the Verona Beach State Park remains closed over
health concerns following a sewage spill last week.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, officials said the discharge from the city of
Oneida's wastewater treatment plant into Oneida Creek, which flows
into Oneida Lake, was less than first thought.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 100,000 to 150,000 gallons was an initial estimate,''
plant Chief Operator Steven Skowron Jr. said. ''(Our best) estimate
now is that less than 50,000 gallons of untreated wastewater
spilled into the creek.''
</P>
<P>
   Verona Beach State Park and the village of Sylvan Beach
voluntarily closed their beaches last week on the advice of the
Oneida County Health Department. The health department advised
people avoid using water from any part of Oneida Lake for any
reason.
</P>
<P>
   While it's possible Verona Beach could reopen later Monday,
officials said they won't be able to determine that until two
consecutive tests show up negative for fecal coliform.
</P>
<P>
   One set of tests showed significantly high levels of coliform,
said a health department Supervising Sanitarian Nick DeRosa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-04-00 0249 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
