<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Waste Weed-Treatment, 1st Ld-Writethru,0233  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHOENIX, N.Y. (AP) - A common weed found along the roadsides of
upstate New York could save this village $1 million if used for the
treatment of waste water sludge.
</P>
<P>
   Under a recent village board proposal, solid sewage filtered out
by the waste water treatment plant would be placed in sand beds
containing phragmites, or ditch weed, whose reeds would absorb
moisture and nutrients from the material. The decomposed sludge
would be hauled from the beds at the plant to a landfill once every
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system - seen by officials as too expensive -
sludge is laid out to dry over sand beds and then brought to the
Oswego County Landfill, two or three times a year.
</P>
<P>
   That operation hasn't been cost efficient. Village officials
estimate that 80 percent to 85 percent of the disposed sludge has
been water, even in the warmer months.
</P>
<P>
   With the weed bed system, water would make up less than 3
percent of the sludge's moisture. The village of Phoenix would save
a substantial amount of money if the material is dried more
thoroughly before it goes to the landfill.
</P>
<P>
   The village currently dumps more than 100 tons of sludge
annually in the county landfill, which charges $50 a ton.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Conservation is
considering the proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
