<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge: Former owner of Ott Chemical site not responsible for cleanup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MUSKEGON, Mich. (AP) - A California company that once owned the
former Ott Chemical facility will not have to pay the cost of
cleaning up pollution at a defunct manufacturing plant in Dalton
Township.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Douglas W. Hillman has approved a consent
decree that absolves Aerojet General Corp. and its local
subsidiary, Cordova Chemical Co. of Michigan, of $100 million in
cleanup costs at the Ott/Story Superfund site in Muskegon County.
</P>
<P>
   Hillman's ruling means another former owner of the Ott facility,
BestFoods Inc., could get stuck with more than $90 million in
cleanup costs not funded by the state of Michigan. If that company
succeeds in its legal battle to avoid paying, however, taxpayers
will get the bill, The Muskegon Chronicle reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Before BestFoods can be ordered to pay for the cleanup, the
government must prove that the Englewood Cliffs, N.J.-based company
was involved enough in the operation of Ott Chemical in the 1960s
to make it liable for environmental problems caused by its Muskegon
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at BestFoods, formerly known as CPC International
Inc., could not be reached for comment by the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Peden, site manager for Cordova Chemical at the former Ott
facility, called the court ruling ''thoughtful and fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It serves to validate our record of exemplary corporate
environmental performance,'' Peden said. ''The road (to this
ruling) has been long and expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   In his Aug. 24 ruling, Hillman said the consent decree proposed
by Aerojet/Cordova, the state of Michigan and the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency was ''fair and reasonable'' and
will ''promote the efficient cleanup of the site.''
</P>
<P>
   BestFoods lawyers had challenged the proposed deal, suggesting
it was unfair and the result of collusion between Aerojet and the
government agencies. BestFoods is expected to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Hillman dismissed the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am satisfied that the government's assessment of
proportional responsibility and amount of damages is rational,'' he
said in his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Previous court rulings determined that the principle source of
contamination at the site was the use of unlined lagoons for
chemical waste disposal from 1959 to 1968. CPC International owned
Ott Chemical during part of that period, Hillman said; Aerojet did
not.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan and EPA officials have been trying since 1981 to make
BestFoods and Aerojet pay for the cleanup. In a case that went all
the way to the U.S. Supreme Court, the federal government claimed
BestFoods and Aerojet were responsible for contamination at the Ott
site because they controlled subsidiaries that owned the facility
at the time pollution occurred.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 Supreme Court ruling in that case limited the
government's ability to hold parent corporations liable for
cleaning up pollution caused by their subsidiaries. That ruling
forced the government to test its case against the court's new
standard for corporate environmental liability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
