<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 10:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boring? N.J. man wrote the book  </HEADLINE>
By WAYNE PARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAPLEWOOD, N.J. (AP) - This is a boring story.
</P>
<P>
   It's about the son of a certified public accountant, a
62-year-old man who lives at home with his mother, spending most of
the day in front of his computer or reading books, waiting for
lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   He's very excited about an upcoming study on how U.S.
Congressmen voted on issues concerning national sovereignty, runs a
public relations business out of his home, and doesn't like to go
to parties.
</P>
<P>
   He maintains a web site called ''The Boring Institute,'' a spoof
on boring things, places and people (see: ''Buttafuoco, Joey'').
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Forrest Gump, boring is as boring does. But don't
dare call Alan Caruba boring.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not a boring person,'' insists Caruba, a former newspaper
reporter and editor. ''I do well over 1,000 radio interviews a
year. I wouldn't be asked back week after week if what I had to say
on various topics was boring.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone should know boring, it's Caruba. His ''Boring
Institute'' web site gets nearly 100,000 hits a month. On it, you
can find everything from the most boring celebrities of the year
(Hillary Clinton took top honors, followed by disc jockey Don Imus,
Bill Bradley and shirtless soccer player Brandi Chastain) to the
most boring films of the year (''Eyes Wide Shut'' and ''The Blair
Witch Project'') and a veritable potpourri of other boring things,
including the presidential conventions.
</P>
<P>
   It started in 1984 when Caruba, a former reporter with the Daily
Record in Morris County, realized how many pop culture lists were
popping up in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were an awful lot of very predictable lists of 'Who's
hot and who's not' and 'Who's in and who's out,' '' he said. ''I
thought the one list that was missing was, 'Who cares?' ''
</P>
<P>
   So he put together a list of the most boring celebrities of the
year, topped that year by Michael Jackson, Andy Rooney and Walter
Mondale.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a lark, I sent it to AP and UPI and Reuters, who instantly
picked it up and put it around the world,'' he said. ''The reason
there's a Boring Institute is you just can't have Alan Caruba
saying these people are boring; you needed an organization to do
it. Since most people have never paid attention to my opinions on
any subject, I've had to rely on these organizational facades.''
</P>
<P>
   But then a weird thing started happening: People started
e-mailing Caruba for advice on how to beat boredom, sharing
complaints about their lives and asking for guidance.
</P>
<P>
   ''People started taking me seriously,'' he said. ''I got so many
requests for information about boredom and how to beat it that I
sat down and wrote my own guide.'' (Nursing homes are a big
customer, he said, displaying letters from senior centers to prove
it.)
</P>
<P>
   His advice is all his own ''common sense,'' although he did say
he ran his suggestions on beating boredom past a psychologist, who
approved. Tips include reading a lot, doing routine chores with a
positive attitude, and getting out and doing something different.
</P>
<P>
   But lest anyone take him too seriously, Caruba decided to run
for president this year as the candidate of the Boring Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've actually had people call me up and ask if I've registered
with their county elections board, which I think is hilarious,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign slogan: ''Elect me, and ignore me.'' The first
thing he plans to do after being inaugurated is install a pool
table in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   He's not worried about splitting the boring vote with Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he's elected, I'm predicting mass suicides because Al Gore
is so unmercifully boring that the prospect of having to listen to
him lecture us as if we were 3-year-olds, stopping to pause between
each word, for four years is enough to make you want to kill
yourself,'' Caruba said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the great benefit of George Bush, who is interesting
because even he doesn't know what's going to come out of his mouth
at any given time,'' Caruba said. ''That makes him fun.''	   
</P>
<P>
 On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Boring Institute: http://www.boringinstitute.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-04-00 1056 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000904.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Store owners: Pennsylvanians cross state line for liquor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PRIMOS, Pa. (AP) - Out-of-state liquor store owners and buyers
aren't sure if state Liquor Control Board agents are enforcing
Pennsylvania's strict law against buying liquor in neighboring
states, but the PLCB leaves no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oh yeah, we're out there. We're looking,'' said PLCB
enforcement agent Sgt. Stacy Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   ''The border patrols work on a regular basis. There is no set
pattern but we do it on a regular basis. We might set up once and
then do it again two weeks later, or we might do it twice in one
week,'' said Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   David Trone, co-owner of Liquor World in Claymont, Del., isn't
convinced. He said the state has given up on enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Zero effort is being made because Pennsylvania has finally
realized that it doesn't make sense to be known as a state that
arrests its innocent citizens for buying a product in their own
country. We live in one country, not 50,'' said Trone.
</P>
<P>
   Liquor World, a 20,000-square-foot store just over the state
line from Lower Chichester, is one of dozens of liquor stores on a
popular sales-tax-free strip in Claymont that seems destined to
attract Pennsylvanians. It even advertises in Pennsylvania
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania state liquor stores are the only place residents
can legally buy wine and spirits for their homes. The commonwealth
taxes the price of liquor with an 18 percent liquor tax and a 6
percent sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Stores outside the state often beat those prices, even though
the Pennsylvania state store system is the largest purchaser of
alcohol in the world. Delaware, for example, has no sales tax,
although it has a tax of $3.75 per gallon of liquor that is more
than 25 percent alcohol. Spirits less than 50 proof have an excise
tax of $2.50 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Buying liquor outside of Pennsylvania and bringing it back
across state lines can be fined in one of two ways.
</P>
<P>
   A violation of the Malt Beverage Tax Act is worth a fine of $10
per can or bottle of beer and $25 for each bottle of wine or
spirits. Violators who default on paying the fine are subject to
not more than five days in jail for each infraction.
</P>
<P>
   Violators can also be cited under Pennsylvania's Liquor Code 491
for violating liquor license laws, which requires a court
appearance and has a sliding fine, Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said the state has changed its enforcement methods, no
longer stopping violators in unmarked vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll go into Delaware or Maryland and monitor a liquor store.
We'll watch and follow people back into Pennsylvania,'' Marshall
said. ''We do not stop anyone until they're across state lines. We
keep them in eyesight until a state police trooper stops and cites
the individual violating the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Harmer, owner of Weaver's Liquors in Elkton, Md., said he
hasn't seen the PLCB since Maryland passed a law requiring agents
to register with the county sheriff's office two weeks before
staking out a liquor store.
</P>
<P>
   ''They haven't notified the sheriff's office in years. The last
time they were supposed to watch my store they never showed up,''
Harmer said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.lcb.state.pa.us/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-04-00 1058 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000904.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Haddonfield students seeking sponsors for college education  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   HADDONFIELD, N.J. (AP) - Two Haddonfield teens are willing to
sell their bodies for a college education.
</P>
<P>
   Luke McCabe and Chris Barrett are offering to be walking
billboards for companies that will sponsor them and contribute
toward their tuition, room and board.
</P>
<P>
   The pair say that as ''spokesguys'' they'll put corporate logos
on their clothes, wear a company's sunglasses, use their golf
clubs, eat their pizza, drink their soda, listen to their music or
drive their cars.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where we go, you go!'' they pledge on their Web site in a
pitch to potential advertisers. ''Sponsor us. We will eat your
cereal even if we're not hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Say, Pepsi were to sponsor us,'' Luke said in an interview
last week. ''We'll get everyone drinking Pepsi, or at least
watching us drink Pepsi. We'll have Pepsi parties.''
</P>
<P>
   They are willing to promote any products that are geared toward
college students, except alcohol and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   They believe they would be the first corporate college
''spokesguys'' in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The pair, who will be seniors this year at Haddonfield Memorial
High School, came up with the idea while touring potential
colleges, and realizing how expensive they are.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California at San Diego is the first choice
for the friends, who would like to go to the same school. Tuition,
room and board there for out-of-state students costs $22,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Luke lives in Haddonfield and Chris lives in nearby Cherry Hill
- both pricey Philadelphia suburbs. They acknowledge that they're
not poor.
</P>
<P>
   ''This isn't a handout,'' said Chris, 18. ''We could go out and
get a student loan or scholarship, but we wanted to try something
new and innovative. We'll be able to work for (the) company while
we're working on our degrees,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California at San Diego offers several
corporate scholarships, said spokeswoman Pat JaCoby. ''They don't
have to go out and find their own corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris and Luke's Web site offers a ''tour'' showing the various
ways the two could advertise for a company while at college. It
begins with pictures of them visiting ''Extremely Expensive U.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair is seen boarding a plane with the headline, ''We will
fly on your planes. We are always going somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Later they're seen heading out surfing, with the words ''Your
Logo Here'' superimposed on a surfboard. Another photo shows them
in a shiny, blue sports car with the promise that ''Your ad will
have prime placement.''
</P>
<P>
   Luke, 17, has agreed to get a tattoo with a company's logo, but
Chris isn't willing to go that far.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Kaufman-Scarborough, an associate professor of marketing
at Rutgers University-Camden, said their idea is ''wonderfully
creative,'' but not without potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''Suppose I'm Domino's Pizza and I sponsor them, then Weight
Watchers come in,'' she said. ''Oftentimes when companies use
someone as a corporate spokesperson, they're very careful that they
represent a certain kind of image.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris and Luke said so far, eight companies have expressed an
interest. Most are ''dot-com'' companies from California.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once we get enough offers we'll see what company it would be
easiest to advertise for, first of all,'' said Luke. ''Then we'll
see the offers and money they want to put out.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to put our cards on the table and see what we can do
for the companies,'' said Chris.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman-Scarborough said companies that want to sponsor the
students would need to draw up very careful agreements with them.
</P>
<P>
   ''They could get a lot of publicity, which would be advantageous
for the company, but the downside would be control possibilities,''
she said. ''Has everything really been thought through?''
</P>
<P>
   ''If I were the student, would I be willing to conform my life
to whatever the corporate wishes of the company would be? Maybe
they wouldn't want me to be in a frat, or would want me to have a
certain major,'' she said. ''They need to think about conformance.
It's almost like the corporation would become the parent.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly, everyone is looking to have their education
financed. It's wonderfully creative,'' said Kaufman-Scarborough.
''If all the issues can be ironed out, there's a possibility
there'd be really good benefits on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris and Luke said their parents think the idea is innovative.
''But also we'll be saving them lots of money,'' said Chris, ''so
who wouldn't be happy?''
</P>
<P>
   On The Net: www.chrisandluke.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
