<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Defends Beatification  </HEADLINE>
By VICTOR L. SIMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Pope John Paul II defended his newly
beatified predecessor on Monday, describing Pope Pius IX as a
misunderstood man who ''never failed to be indulgent toward his
enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   The noble-born, 19th-century Pius took delight in preaching ''as
a simple priest'' and going about to ''meet the people on the
streets of Rome,'' John Paul told pilgrims who lingered in Rome
after Sunday's beatifications.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul beatified Pius alongside the 20th-century's
much-beloved Pope John XXIII and three other church figures before
an estimated 100,000-strong crowd in St. Peter's Square.
</P>
<P>
   Beatification, the last step before possible sainthood,
officially sets the subjects as models for the faith.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish groups, an Israeli Cabinet minister and others protested
the recognition of Pius -- many calling it a misstep in the progress
John Paul's own 22-year papacy has made in Catholic-Jewish
relations.
</P>
<P>
   History's longest-serving pontiff, Pius was a rigid
traditionalist who maintained restrictions on Jews in Rome's ghetto
and condoned the taking of a Jewish-born boy, 6-year-old Edgardo
Mortara, who had been baptized without knowledge of his family.
</P>
<P>
   The Simon Wiesenthal Center kept up the protests Monday, saying
the beatification followed other, recent Vatican actions that upset
Jews, including the 1998 canonization of Edith Stein, a Jewish-born
nun who was killed in a death camp. Some Jewish leaders charged
that Catholics were denying Jews' disproportionate suffering in the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are extremely worried about this direction,'' said Shimon
Samuels, the Jewish organization's director of international
relations in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ''It violates the spirit created by His Holiness' pilgrimage to
the Holy Land and of other statements made by John Paul that in
this Jubilee year the slate should be cleaned of all controversies
in the Catholic-Jewish relationship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Paul visited Israel and Palestinian territories in March, a
highlight of a papacy that has seen the Holy See open diplomatic
relations with Israel and John Paul apologize for the historic
wrongs of Catholics toward Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The 80-year-pontiff did not directly respond Monday to the
criticism of the beatification.
</P>
<P>
   But he did say that Pius IX was ''particularly attentive about
the Holy Land,'' and had wanted to re-establish the Roman Catholic
patriarchate in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In greeting the present-day patriarch, Archbishop Michel Sabbah,
the pope said he recalled ''with affection and gratitude the holy
places and the people I met during my recent pilgrimage in the Holy
Land.''
</P>
<P>
   John Paul's remarks on Pius' beatification Sunday stressed his
predecessor's service to the faith during a difficult and often
violent time of growing nationalism and anti-clericalism.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke Monday of Pius' indulgence in the face of ''attacks and
slander.''
</P>
<P>
   Jews and other critics recall Pius in far different terms. They
cite contemporary accounts in which Pius allegedly referred to Jews
as ''dogs'' and quelled Jewish leaders' protests of the taking of
6-year-old Edgardo by threatening to force them ''back into their
holes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 1158 </TRAILER>
