<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 12:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Suppresses Political Dissent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Two years ago, a band of dissidents tried to form
China's first legal opposition party under communist rule. Now, its
34 leading members are in jail, prisoners of a ceaseless campaign
to prevent challenges to the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   The China Democracy Party's surprising emergence and quick
suppression underscores China's scant political progress despite
two decades of free-market reforms and loosening social controls,
New York-based Human Rights Watch said in a report for release
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report was timed to coincide with Chinese President Jiang
Zemin's five-day visit to New York for a U.N. summit. At the
summit, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has encouraged world
leaders to pledge to ratify basic U.N. covenants, human rights
agreements among them, if their countries have not done so.
</P>
<P>
   ''As President Jiang is feted as an economic reformer during his
visit, admirers should remember that in China, promoting political
reform remains a hazardous occupation,'' Sydney Jones, Human Rights
Watch's Asia director, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of a brief period of political tolerance and a
China visit by President Clinton, a group of dissidents publicly
launched the China Democracy Party in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Within six months, when the government jailed its most prominent
leaders, the party attracted 200 members and had organizations in
24 provinces, Human Rights Watch said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous attempts to form political parties, China
Democracy Party members tried to register openly with authorities,
appealing to rights under China's constitution and U.N. treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers included veteran dissidents, who combined their
organizing skills with the Internet to publicize the group.
</P>
<P>
   One founding member, Wu Yilong, made a 16-day nationwide
recruiting tour that the report called instrumental in setting up
provincial party groups.
</P>
<P>
   Wu did not use phones to contact potential members, often known
dissidents, for fear of police taps, and he did not sleep in hotels
because police routinely check registers, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
   The communist government quickly signaled its intolerance and
tightened rules on registering social groups.
</P>
<P>
   President Jiang vowed in December to eliminate groups fomenting
instability -- a euphemism for challenges to party rule -- demanding
they be ''nipped in the bud.''
</P>
<P>
   In a series of trials that began in December 1998 and continued
into this year, courts jailed 34 China Democracy Party members for
subversion, Human Rights Watch said. Four others fled into exile,
it added.
</P>
<P>
   China has 200,000 social groups officially registered with the
Ministry of Civil Affairs, but not one independent political party,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch urged Beijing to release the 34 party
members, rescind laws that undermine freedoms of association and
expression and ratify two U.N. covenants on political and economic
rights that China has already signed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 1201 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
