<DOCNO> APW20000904.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 12:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> For spot movement Mon. Sept. 4 for Tues. Sept. 5  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newcomb is a scenic, but sleepy Adirondack Mountain community
that is little more than a dot on the map between other dots on the
map like Long Lake and Winebrook Hills.
</P>
<P>
   It is an unlikely place, then, for a case that could have
ramifications throughout New York for both the way municipalities
tax property owners and how school districts spend taxpayer money.
</P>
<P>
   The Newcomb Central School District has had to defend in court
its plans to build a $1.2 million indoor swimming pool. The
proposal for the six-lane, competition-sized pool is one phase of a
$3.3 million expansion plan that includes improvements to the
school's gymnasium, stage and lockerrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Like hundreds of other districts around the state, Newcomb
Central wants to take advantage of a soon-to-expire state program
which boosts the state's portion of building construction aid by 10
percent. In January, voters in the school district approved the
building plans, 158-101.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Finch, Pruyn and Co., which owns 53,000 acres of mostly
forestland in the town of Newcomb. The Glens Falls-based paper
company cuts timber on the land for its mills and also rents the
property to hunting and fishing organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Finch, Pruyn argued in court that a $1.2 million swimming pool
for a school with 71 students in grades kindergarten through 12 is
''excessive and lavish.'' The company also is suing the town,
contending that its homestead tax provisions are rigged so that
residential property owners pay little tax and the few commercial
interests in town pay an unfairly high share of tax.
</P>
<P>
   A homeowning resident of Newcomb will pay about $22 a year for
the pool, Finch, Pruyn spokesman Mark Behan said. The company, by
comparison, will pay $15,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Finch, Pruyn said it challenged the pool in court after it
became clear to the company that town and school district officials
would not budge on their pool plan. School leaders say the pool
will not only be invaluable at teaching youngsters in a town filled
with lakes and waterways to swim, but can also be used by adults in
town as a recreational facility.
</P>
<P>
   ''We proposed alternatives - it would be less expensive to buy
every child a membership in a local YMCA for 10 years and to
provide transportation for that child than it would be to do that
project,'' Behan said. ''This is an excessively expensive way to
provide that service (teaching youngsters to swim).''
</P>
<P>
   A state Supreme Court justice rejected the company's arguments,
saying an appeal the Finch, Pruyn filed before the state's
education commissioner questioning the appropriateness of the
Newcomb expenditure should be decided first. But Finch, Pruyn says
it will appeal the Supreme Court justice's determination to the
Appellate Division of state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Kearns, the superintendent of the Newcomb district, said
school officials throughout the state should be worried because if
Finch, Pruyn is successful in Newcomb, any corporate entity could
follow its lead and challenge public appropriations in the
communities in which they pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ''The question is, once the will of the people has been
expressed legally, can you go over their heads and say what is
lavish and extravagant?'' she said. ''Who defines lavish?''
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent said Finch, Pruyn is pursuing the case with a
deeper purpose in mind, to try to claim for ''big business'' the
right to oversee a government entity's budget.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not unusual to try these cases in very small, vulnerable
districts,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has cost the district more than $30,000 to fend off
the Finch, Pruyn challenge, money the superintendent said would be
better spent on educating students.
</P>
<P>
   Kearns said Finch, Pruyn (pronounced PRYNE) is misrepresenting
itself as shouldering the brunt of the school's budget. In fact,
the company paid 4.5 percent of the budget for the 1999-2000 school
year - about $90,000 - or roughly the same amount as the town's
residential taxpayers, according to the superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   The state of New York, which has 62,000 acres of land in the
town, paid about $1.7 million or 85 percent of the school's budget,
Kearns said.
</P>
<P>
   Finch, Pruyn also has asked state Education Commissioner Richard
Mills to overturn the results of the January election authorizing
construction of the pool. The commissioner has the power to throw
out the results of elections which are not properly conducted, but
Kearns said she doubts Finch, Pruyn can show that either the budget
balloting was improper or the proposed expenditures inappropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Education Department spokesman Tom Dunn said no decision is
expected from the commissioner until late October or early
November.
</P>
<P>
   The Adirondack Council, an environmentally minded lobbying group
in Albany, said it is watching the Newcomb case closely because of
its ramifications both inside the Adirondack Park and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The state School Boards Association is also keeping an eye on
the case, its spokesman David Ernst said.
</P>
<P>
   ''To permit one taxpayer in a district to overturn, in effect, a
vote by a majority of taxpayers or to nullify what they approved
would not be in the best interests of children,'' Ernst said.
''They say 'swimming pool,' but who's to say it couldn't be any
expenditure that some taxpayers are unhappy about?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-04-00 1206 </TRAILER>
