<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monmouth University freshmen move into hotel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WEST LONG BRANCH, N.J. (AP) - Unexpectedly high enrollment and a
shortage of dormitory rooms has forced Monmouth University to look
to a nearby hotel to house incoming freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   The 120 students - about 10 percent of the incoming first-year
class - moved into their rooms at the Esplanade Hotel on Sunday,
and feelings were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The accommodations here are much better, but I am a little
disappointed I am not on campus,'' Nicole Sagui told the Asbury
Park Press of Neptune for Monday's editions. ''I'd rather be in a
dorm, and my campus experience may now be a little bit different.''
</P>
<P>
   The hotel has a computer room, a pool, maid service, air
conditioning, and each room has a private bathroom. The
university's 13 dormitories, lack most of that - including air
conditioning - and students share a common bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the unconventional housing, university spokeswoman Susan
Doctorian said Monmouth is doing what it can to make sure the
freshmen at the Esplanade have a first-year experience comparable
to their on-campus counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   She said the students, most of whom will have to remain there at
least through the first semester, will pay the same housing rate as
students on campus. They are the only occupants of the 100-room
hotel, which is slated to become an assisted living facility.
</P>
<P>
   A shuttle service will run during the week as late as 11:30 p.m.
Twenty-four hour security also has been provided, and the school is
planning to hold special events to keep students active.
</P>
<P>
   ''The response from both students and parents has been
overwhelmingly positive. Once they saw the accommodations, they all
responded in a positive way. We have had no complaints,'' Doctorian
said. ''Actually, we feel the students may really bond here and not
want to move back to campus, which might not be a good thing
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Incoming freshman Jackie Chafe said her main concern is the
distance to campus.
</P>
<P>
   ''It bothers me just a little to be living out here,'' she said.
''It's nice, but I feel I might be missing out on some of the
action and life on campus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
