<HEADLINE> Parole hearing scheduled for John Lennon's killer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The man who shot and killed John Lennon
outside his New York City apartment in 1980 is scheduled to have
his first parole hearing next month.
</P>
<P>
   A parole board is tentatively set to interview Mark David
Chapman at Attica state prison sometime in October, state Division
of Parole spokesman Tom Grant said Monday. Chapman is serving a 20
years-to-life sentence at Attica for killing the former Beatle.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman gunned down Lennon outside the Dakota, a famous
apartment building in Manhattan, on Dec. 8, 1980, when the musician
and his wife, Yoko Ono, were coming home from a late-night
recording session.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman, 45 is eligible for a parole hearing because he is
approaching the end of his minimum sentence of 20 years. If parole
is approved, Chapman could be released in December.
</P>
<P>
   Chapman, a clerk in the prison's law library, has been
disciplined for only minor infractions behind bars. He also has
expressed remorse for killing Lennon, telling an interviewer in
1990: ''It was an end of innocence for that time. And I regret
being the one that ended it.''
</P>
<P>
   But inmate advocate Robert Gangi of the Correctional Association
of New York predicted there was ''not a chance'' of Chapman getting
parole.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each case should be handled individually,'' Gangi told the
Daily News, ''but anyone convicted of the murder of a famous person
is probably unlikely to ever get parole.'''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Ono will likely offer a victim-impact statement before the
hearing, according to her spokesman, Elliot Mintz.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure she will have something to say on the subject,''
Mintz told the Daily News.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
