<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Suspends Kosovo Jail Director  </HEADLINE>
By MERITA DHIMGJOKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOSOVSKA MITROVICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The chief U.N.
administrator of Kosovo announced Monday that he had suspended the
director of a detention center after 15 Kosovo Serbs escaped from
the facility and warned that other U.N. personnel could also be
disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ''The escape is under heavy investigation,'' Bernard Kouchner
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's easy to come from the international community and not be
responsible,'' said Kouchner, addressing past criticism of lax U.N.
performance in Kosovo. ''They will be responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner said he felt, ''humiliated, frustrated and guilty,
really guilty'' about the escapes Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Ivanovic, a local Serb leader, said that several of the
prisoners who escaped from the detention center in northern Kosovo
after overpowering the guards reportedly had fled out of Kosovo,
which remains a Serbian province despite U.N. and NATO
administration, and into Serbia proper.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen Kosovo Serbs, most of them facing charges of genocide or
crimes against humanity, fled from the U.N. prison in the primarily
Serb part of the divided city of Kosovska Mitrovica. Two were
caught quickly, but the other 13 remain at large.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt Monday to transfer the remaining Serbs from the jail
in Kosovska Mitrovica stalled after angry Serbs blocked the road
leading to the facility.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. police loaded about 15 Serb prisoners into vans for
transfer to an undisclosed detention facility. But the effort ended
after about 100 Serbs gathered outside, blocking NATO and U.N.
police vehicles inside the jail yard.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was defused after Serb civilians volunteered to
ride with U.N. police in the empty vans so they could be driven out
of the city without fear of attack.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, hundreds of NATO-led peacekeepers and U.N. police used
dogs to track the escapees through a wooded area near the jail.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. spokeswoman Susan Manuel called the incident ''extremely
serious'' and said it would damage the reputation of NATO-led
peacekeepers and the United Nations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The men had been held since NATO-led troops took over the
southern Serb province and have been awaiting trial as U.N.
officials struggled to organize a justice system.
</P>
<P>
   ''Confidence of the Serb people in the justice system in Kosovo
is exceptionally low. Those who have been sentenced prematurely
will resort to desperate means, do anything to escape an unjust
verdict without a fair trial,'' Ivanovic said.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials and NATO peacekeepers have controlled Kosovo
since June 1999, since the end of a 78-day air war that forced
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to end his crackdown on
ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The escape occurred when a U.N. policeman was returning a
prisoner to his cell after the man made a phone call. The man's
cellmates overpowered the policeman, beat him and threatened him
with a gun that had been smuggled into the prison, a U.N. statement
said. They snatched the guard's keys and freed detainees from other
cells.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
