<HEADLINE> Five Iranians arrested in paint throwing incidents near the U.N.  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE ROTH
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Four Iranians were arrested for throwing yellow
paint and another for disorderly conduct in separate incidents near
the United Nations, one involving the Iranian president, police
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests by a joint city and federal terrorist task force
came as more than 150 heads of state began arriving for this week's
UN Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Reza Eskandari, 44, was arrested at 4:10 p.m. Sunday for
throwing yellow paint at a car carrying Iranian President Mohammed
Khatami and Prime Minister Amir Abbas Hoveyda. The attack happened
at 53rd Street and the FDR Drive, shortly after the delegation's
motorcade left the United Nations building, said Det. Madeleine
Galindo, a police spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Police Officer Guy Braun said that in a second incident, Sedigh
Hamid, 42, and Mohammed Reza, 44, were arrested at 5 p.m. Sunday
for throwing yellow paint inside the lobby of the United Nations
Plaza Hotel, Braun said. The Iranian delegation is staying at the
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In a third incident, 44-year-old Akbar Parizanani was arrested
soon after for throwing yellow paint in a plastic balloon at the
outside of the hotel, Braun said. Parizanani was caught by a police
officer, who suffered minor injuries in the ensuing scuffle.
Parizanani was taken to Bellevue Hospital for a psychiatric
evaluation because he appeared to be emotionally disturbed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a fourth disturbance near the hotel Sunday, Hojjat Hassany
was arrested for disorderly conduct after he got into an argument
and scuffle with several people at 44th Street and Second Avenue.
Police said they did not know Hassany's age.
</P>
<P>
   Charges in the incidents were not immediately known, Braun said.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not know the significance of the yellow paint, but a
spokesman for the National Council of Resistance of Iran said
yellow is ''the color of dismay, the color of disapproval. It shows
the hatred of people against him.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Khatami is so hated in Iran and outside of Iran because of his
abhorrent record of human rights,'' council spokesman Alireza
Jararzadeh told The Associated Press on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   He denied any involvement by the Paris-based group, which bills
itself as Iran's parliament-in-exile. But the group sent a press
release about Sunday's paint attacks to the AP in Switzerland,
where similar paint attacks on Iranian officials were carried out
earlier this year at a gathering of world leaders in Davos.
</P>
<P>
   The council organized U.N. protests last year at which eggs were
thrown at the Iranian delegation.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Khatami was at the United Nations meeting with
several hundred Iranian-Americans. A call seeking comment about the
paint attacks from the Iranian mission to the United Nations was
not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the other incidents, there were also three
separate bomb threats against the hotel, but the suspicious
packages were found to be harmless, police said.
</P>
<P>
   At least 91 demonstrations are planned for the gathering of
world leaders. The Sept. 6-8 summit is expected to attract more
than 150 heads of state and government - the largest number of
world leaders ever gathered in one city in history, said Police
Commissioner Bernard Kerik.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials say they are confident the 41,000-strong
department - the largest in the nation - can handle any situation,
and they say there will not be a repeat of last fall's WTO
gathering in Seattle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
