<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Abdullah Seeks Mideast Peace Role  </HEADLINE>
By JAMAL HALA
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- As far as Israel is concerned, Jordan is no
longer the Arab friend it was under the late King Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   When Hussein's son, King Abdullah II, ascended to Jordan's
throne last year, he quickly chose more Arab-leaning policies than
the late king, who had been famously friendly with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it appears, Abdullah has decided his choice was a mistake.
A trip to Israel last month gave the first hint of a move to bring
Jordan off the sidelines, back into Israel's good graces -- and back
into the thick of the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains to be seen whether his efforts to switch gears
are sufficient and in time to protect Jordan's interests.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jordan feels that it has been marginalized with Egypt, Israel
and the Palestinians being the key players in Middle East
peacemaking,'' said Jordanian political scientist Labib Kamhawi.
''Therefore, Jordan is trying to make an entry through Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has legitimate reasons for wanting a role in the process.
Abdullah's kingdom is home to 44 percent of the 3.5 million
Palestinian refugees who have lost property and business in Middle
East wars since the creation of Israel in 1948. If violence erupts
in the West Bank over the snail-paced peace process, it could spill
over into Jordan's predominantly Palestinian population.
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah spoke to the editors of Jordan's four daily newspapers
before heading on a foreign trip that was to include talks with
President Clinton at the U.N. Millennium Summit in New York. In a
transcript the papers published, the king said Jordan has ''vital
interests'' in the refugee issue and would ''cling to their right
to return and to compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Jordan's ruling Hashemite family, descended from Islam's
Prophet Mohammed, is traditional caretaker of Muslim holy shrines
in east Jerusalem -- the main sticking point blocking a final
Palestinian-Israeli accord. And Jordan has the longest Arab border
with a would-be Palestinian state and must share an already
inadequate regional water resources with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   When Abdullah visited Israel, he became the only Arab head of
state to go to the Jewish nation since the collapse of the
Israeli-Palestinian summit at Camp David. His visit was a bold move
reminiscent of his late father.
</P>
<P>
   But his trip drew a cool welcome from Israelis. For Abdullah is
not Hussein, the man whose frequent visits and personal attachment
to the Israeli people and their leaders allowed him to broker at
least two interim Israeli-Palestinian peace accords and sign a
peace accord of his own with Israel. In fact, some Israelis
perceive Abdullah's policies as pro-Palestinian.
</P>
<P>
   Days after visiting Israel, Abdullah sent his prime minister
after hard-line Jordanian unionists affiliated with Muslim
fundamentalist and leftist groups opposed to peace with Israel. The
prime minister, Ali Abu-Ragheb, warned the unionists in a public
meeting on Monday that he will not tolerate their anti-Israel
rhetoric, saying it ''violated the law'' and harmed the ''peace
treaty which we respect and are keen to protect.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Jordan is an important pillar of the peace process and when we
talk about a comprehensive peace, Jordan must be incorporated,''
Abu-Ragheb told foreign media correspondents last week.
</P>
<P>
   Since ascending to the throne in February 1999, Abdullah has
kept Israel at arm's length while trying to restore Jordan's ties
with its erstwhile Gulf Arab bankrollers. They ostracized the
kingdom for its perceived pro-Iraq tilt during the 1990-91 Gulf
crisis over Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Abdullah was responding to concerns that Hussein's
alliance with Israel brought cash-strapped Jordan few economic
dividends. A recession is exacerbating Jordan's economic woes
stemming from $7 billion in foreign debt, the loss of its Iraqi
trade partner in 1990 and the end of donations from oil-rich Gulf
Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   These days Egypt -- the first Arab country to sign a peace treaty
with Israel, in 1979 -- is the main Arab peace mediator. Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat has tilted toward Egypt because of its
historical support for the Palestinians and because the most
populous Arab country has considerable sway over Middle East
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has visited Egypt at least six times since the collapse
of Camp David on July 25 but has made no stops in Jordan. Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak did visit Jordan, but just once. And
Clinton visited Egypt, but not Jordan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
