<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bride content with TV wedding  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MORAVIA, N.Y. (AP) - At least Melanie Nelson can say she picked
her own groom, even if all the other parts of her upcoming wedding
were determined by strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, 27, of Moravia in the Finger Lakes area and Peter
Ginsberg, 28, of Long Island will wed Wednesday on the NBC Today
Show. As winners of a 12-part series ''Today Ties The Knot,'' every
aspect of their estimated $45,000 wedding has been chosen by
viewers via the Internet and paid for by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't mind losing control of my wedding,'' she said. ''One
of our mothers would have taken control anyway ... and we're
getting the royal treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC teamed up with TheKnot.com to orchestrate the wedding and
bring more users to the NBC and TheKnot Web sites. Nelson and
Ginsberg found out they won the wedding contest on June 27. More
than 1,000 couples applied.
</P>
<P>
   A different aspect of the wedding has been decided every week by
viewers. Everything but the honeymoon has been decided - and that
will be decided this Tuesday and announced Wednesday at the
wedding. Nelson is hoping the audience chooses Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who called the wedding series a ''fairy tale,'' said the
Today Show viewers have good taste and voted for the majority of
her favorite picks. She loves everything, she said, but would have
preferred different invitations and a different cake, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson doesn't have cold feet about getting married to Ginsberg,
she said, but stage fright is setting in.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have the normal jitters,'' she said. ''Am I going to trip
and fall? Am I going to stumble on my vows?''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is getting her master's in psychology at Columbia
University and Ginsberg is a trial lawyer in New York City. Money
is tight for them, Nelson said, so the free wedding and honeymoon
are a blessing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
