<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Troops Repulse Rebels  </HEADLINE>
By DILSHIKA JAYAMAHA
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- Fighter jets pounded Sri Lanka's
northern Jaffna Peninsula and government troops repulsed a Tamil
rebel counterattack Monday in a massive government offensive. At
least 344 combatants have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 other soldiers and rebels were wounded in the
government offensive that began Sunday around the city of Jaffna,
which the rebels have been trying to take since April and make the
capital of a Tamil homeland in northern and eastern Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   The military said its offensive had succeeded. It said the
rebels were pushed from areas they captured in April and May in the
insurgents' offensive that brought them within miles of Jaffna city
before they were halted.
</P>
<P>
   ''The aim behind our operation ... is to regain areas that we
had lost to the terrorists and also to create a bigger buffer zone
to protect the city of Jaffna,'' military spokesman Brig. Sanath
Karunaratne told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have achieved our aim,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The army said that 114 soldiers had been killed and 766 wounded
since Sunday in the assault, led by MiG-27 jets, meant to increase
the security around Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   More than 230 rebels were killed in the army's ''Operation
Sunrise'' and at least 300 were wounded, military officials said,
citing intercepts of rebel radio conversations.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting has killed 1,380 combatants on both sides since
April.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's fighting erupted as the army tried to consolidate newly
captured areas, said Karunaratne. The rebels attacked the new army
defenses twice, but ''failed to dislodge the security forces,''
Karunaratne said.
</P>
<P>
   Government troops faced tough resistance as they advanced
simultaneously on five fronts in the peninsula. But troops were
able to retake an area several miles east of Jaffna city, said
Karunaratne.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting is the fiercest since May, when the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam rebels began a drive to take Jaffna and
forced the military to withdraw into the city, which the rebels
controlled from 1990 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The military launched Sunday's attacks about 15 miles east of
Jaffna to dislodge rebels from their positions.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels said on their Web site that they resisted the attack,
but did not give their casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Independent accounts of the fighting are not available as
neither side allows journalists into the war zone. The government
imposed media censorship during the rebel advance in May.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam rebels have fought
government forces since 1983 to carve out a Tamil homeland. More
than 62,000 people have been killed in the civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's battle forced thousands of civilians to flee their
homes to escape artillery fire, rebel sources said, quoting reports
from Jaffna. One source said at least 15,000 civilians had left the
area as of early Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But the army said civilians had vacated the region during the
April-May battles.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   ON THE NET:
</P>
<P>
   Tamil rebels: http://www.eelamweb.com
</P>
<P>
   Sri Lankan government: http://www.priu.gov.lk
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
