<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Considers Amnesty for Exiles  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- A bill that would grant amnesty to Iranians
who fled the country because of anti-government activities or ties
to outlawed political parties is aimed at promoting national
reconciliation and attracting badly needed investments, a lawmaker
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow such Iranians to return without fear of
prosecution or punishment, said Elyas Hazrati, one of 40 lawmakers
who signed the bill. Only those who have used violence against the
state are excluded from the amnesty deal.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was submitted to the parliament, or Majlis, on Sunday.
To become law, it requires a majority vote there and ratification
by the hard-line Guardian Council, which acts as an upper chamber
of parliament. A Majlis vote is expected in November, after
committee debate, Hazrati said.
</P>
<P>
   Hazrati, a reformist lawmaker, said general amnesty legislation
has been a goal of the reform movement led by President Mohammad
Khatami. It wasn't clear whether it would become another point of
contention between reformists and hard-liners, whose control of the
Guardian Council could block the bill even if the
reformist-dominated Majlis approves it.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bill seeks to promote the culture of reconciliation and
not revenge, something that our country badly needs,'' Hazrati
said, adding that ''our national interests require us to facilitate
the return of expatriates.''
</P>
<P>
   He said most of the estimated 3 million Iranians who fled Iran
following the 1979 Islamic revolution were top scientists,
university teachers and wealthy individuals whose return could
bring tens of billions of dollars in investments as well as
technology to help Iran develop.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraq-based armed Iranian opposition group, the Mujahedeen
Khalq, which seeks the violent overthrow of Iran's Islamic
government, is excluded from the bill. The group fought against
Iran in the 1980-88 Iran-Iraq war and still carries out strikes on
Iranian soil from bases across the border in Iraq.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 1457 </TRAILER>
