   Two servicemen from Russia's Federal Security Service, successor
to the KGB, were seriously wounded when their vehicle was fired on
after it ran over a mine near the town of Tsotsin-Yurt in eastern
Chechnya, military officials said. Twelve suffered slight wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials claimed they killed seven rebels in the
ensuing gunfight, but such claims are difficult to confirm and both
sides exaggerate the others' casualties.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments, a school principal, her parents and her
sister were killed by unknown attackers at their home in Grozny,
the Interfax news agency reported Monday. The report gave only the
name of the teacher, Olga Klimova, and said her husband had been
abducted last year.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops returned to Chechnya last fall to suppress the
republic's separatist government after being driven out at the end
of a 1994-96 war. The Russian military controls large areas of
Chechnya, but appears to be far from defeating the rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 1548 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000904.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Defends Crackdown  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) -- Myanmar's military government cracked
down on the opposition National League for Democracy and raided its
headquarters because of concerns it might be linked to
anti-government ''terrorists,'' a top official told foreign
diplomats Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Response from the party was not available because all its
leaders were being held incommunicado at their homes. But the top
U.S. diplomat in Myanmar -- also known as Burma -- characterized an
earlier government suggestion of the opposition party's ties to
terrorists as a fabrication.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Foreign Minister Khin Maung Win made the terrorism
suggestion at a series of meetings at the foreign ministry to give
the government's version of its latest confrontation with the
National League for Democracy. The standoff began Aug. 24, when
government security forces stopped opposition leader Aung San Suu
Kyi and 14 of her colleagues from traveling to the countryside to
do political organizing.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats provided accounts of the meetings to The Associated
Press on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   At one of Monday's foreign ministry briefings, the government
accused an ethnic rebel group, the Karen National Union, and an
exile opposition group, the All Burma Students' Democratic Front,
of conspiring with National League for Democracy youths. It said
the groups were trying to smuggle five remote-controlled bombs into
the capital to carry out terrorist activities in August and
September.
</P>
<P>
   The statement indicated that a dozen ''terrorists'' who came
from the area of the Thai border were still at large. It said that
to prevent possible acts of terrorism, the National League for
Democracy office had to be temporarily closed to carry out
necessary investigations.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Charge d'Affaires Priscilla Clapp, contacted from Bangkok,
Thailand, said the charge that the NLD is linked to alleged
terrorist groups is ''a malicious fabrication.'' She pointed out
that the party has been carrying out nonviolent political
activities for more than a decade, and that Suu Kyi won the 1991
Nobel peace prize for such work.
</P>
<P>
   The NLD's most recent confrontation with Myanmar's iron-fisted
government began when the security forces barred Suu Kyi from
proceeding past a suburb of the capital, Yangon. Suu Kyi and her
group refused to return to Yangon and camped out for nine days in
their two vehicles in a muddy, mosquito-infested field.
</P>
<P>
   One of those involved in the roadside confrontation, party
Deputy Chairman Tin Oo, said Saturday that authorities had forcibly
returned the group to the capital the night before. Police chased
away reporters and sealed off his house before he could provide
details.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as they were returned to the capital, all members of the
party's central executive committee were locked in their homes and
the party's headquarters was raided. The headquarters remained
closed and occupied Monday by security personnel who have been
removing documents.
</P>
<P>
   Although sealed off from visitors, Suu Kyi is in good health
inside her Yangon compound, a party member said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Suu Kyi has led the opposition movement in Myanmar since 1988,
when the military quashed pro-democracy demonstrations and asserted
its authoritarian rule. She has invited foreign pressure on the
military regime and has been rebuffed repeatedly in attempts to
hold a dialogue with Myanmar's rulers.
</P>
<P>
   The military held an election in 1990, but refused to allow
parliament to convene after the NLD won a landslide victory. Since
then, the party's members have been arrested and harassed.
</P>
<P>
   Clapp said police have barred diplomats from even approaching
the homes of the NLD party leaders, whose telephone lines have been
cut.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government says it's not house arrest, but to us it looks
like house arrest,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 1551 </TRAILER>
