<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYPD officer's son dies from gunshot wound  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW WINDSOR, N.Y. (AP) - Police were investigating whether the
5-year-old son of a New York City police officer fatally shot
himself after grabbing his father's revolver from the top of a
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   David Reveille died Sunday after being shot in the stomach in
his family's home 50 miles northwest of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Police in New Windsor said Monday they were investigating
reports that the boy used a stool to reach up to the top of the
family's refrigerator, where his father had placed his loaded
off-duty weapon, a .38 caliber revolver.
</P>
<P>
   The father, 38-year-old David Reveille, is an eight-year veteran
of the city police. He reportedly placed the weapon on the
refrigerator after returning home from a night shift.
</P>
<P>
   Police were told the boy's father was sleeping in an upstairs
bedroom and that his mother was upstairs working when the gun went
off in the first-floor living room area. The boy's wound appeared
to be self-inflicted, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Police did not disclose whether the boy's three sisters - aged
2, 4 and 6 - witnessed the shooting. The investigation was
continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency workers called to the scene helped airlift the boy to
Good Samaritan Hospital in Suffern, where he was pronounced dead.
</P>
<P>
   The family was greeted at the hospital by New York City police
officers and New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, said Veronica
Barton, administrative supervisor for Good Samaritan Hospital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
