<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pair charged with murder, arson, burglary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Buffalo police Sunday charged two men with
arson and murder in the fire death of a West Seneca tavern owner.
</P>
<P>
   Police say 20-year-old Johnathan Spaeth of Sloan and 22-year-old
Daniel Mariani of Buffalo set the fire to cover the robbery and
assault of William Metzger, the 65-year-old owner of the Goldmine
Tavern.
</P>
<P>
   The two are charged with second-degree murder, first-degree
burglary and first-degree arson.
</P>
<P>
   Spaeth and Mariani reportedly entered the tavern after it closed
about 2:30 a.m. and confronted Metzger in his apartment above the
bar, beating and robbing him. The men then reportedly set the
building on fire before fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   Though Metzger died from smoke inhalation, his death was ruled a
homicide because he had been beaten up.
</P>
<P>
   West Seneca is 7 miles east of Buffalo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
