<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Heads: EU Expansion on Track  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- German leaders insisted Monday that the drive to
enlarge the European Union remains on track despite an EU
commissioner's suggestion of a referendum on whether eastern
European nations should join.
</P>
<P>
   Guenther Verheugen, a German who is the EU commissioner
overseeing enlargement talks with a dozen nations, set off a furor
Saturday by saying that a referendum on expansion would force
German politicians to make their case more clearly to citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder told German ambassadors from around
the world gathered in Berlin on Monday that Germany supports the
speedy expansion of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer, in remarks at the same
forum, noted that there is no provision for a national referendum
in the German constitution and ruled out the idea of a plebiscite
on EU expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said the notion that Germany would change its
constitution to allow a referendum on having Poland, Czech Republic
and Hungary and other countries join the 15-nation European Union
was ''totally unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   With Germany in the throes of a national debate on how to combat
a surge of neo-Nazi violence and anti-foreigner sentiment,
Verheugen's remarks on taking the question of EU expansion to the
people came at a sensitive time.
</P>
<P>
   Also, referendums have been taboo in Germany since Adolf Hitler
used them to consolidate Nazi power in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have shown most Germans are reluctant to embrace Poland
and other East European candidates as European Union members,
partly because they fear an influx of cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
   ''How a referendum in Germany would turn out is easy to imagine,
given the anti-foreigner sentiment that is rife and claims new
victims daily,'' said Hans Modrow, East Germany's last communist
premier and now a member of parliament from the ex-communist Party
of Democratic Socialism.
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder insisted a new, more multicultural German society
is developing, and he urged his diplomats to ''convey abroad the
image of an enlightened and tolerant Germany that is open to the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not tolerate xenophobia and neo-Nazi violence in
Germany,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer acknowledged that the case for European Union expansion
needs to be made to the people -- particularly in eastern Germany,
shut off by communism for decades and a breeding ground for
anti-foreigner sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said the first group of new EU members should join by
2005 at the latest and include Poland.
</P>
<P>
   The organization has set no entry dates, and the leading
hopefuls say they would like to join by 2003. However, a leading
German business group this year argued that enlargement should be
delayed until at least 2004-2006.
</P>
<P>
   EU enlargement talks began in 1998 with Hungary, Poland, the
Czech Republic, Estonia, Slovenia and Cyprus. This year, Bulgaria,
Romania, Latvia, Lithuania, Slovakia and Malta were added to the
list. Turkey is also a candidate, but entry talks are not expected
to open for some years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 1801 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000904.0091 </DOCNO>
