<HEADLINE> Aborigines Plan Olympic Protest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- An Aboriginal protest organizer said he
plans to set up a camp in a park next to the Olympic site in
Homebush, even if police refuse to give him permission.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Close said he plans to occupy Bicentennial Park on Sept.
13 with about 50 Aborigines, and would welcome being arrested to
attract attention to indigenous issues.
</P>
<P>
   Close said Monday his group would be prepared if police tried to
break up the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the boys will have spears and nulla-nullas (Aboriginal
clubs) with them,'' he said. ''We'll go in fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said Monday night that protests at Olympic Park were
unlikely to be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Close also said he is organizing an indigenous ceremony in
Parramatta at sunset Thursday to welcome Olympic visitors with
song, dance and a fashion parade.
</P>
<P>
   Police have granted another group of Aboriginal activists
permission to protest outside Sydney Airport in the days leading up
to the Olympic Games. Protesters will form a human chain in streets
near the airport on Sept. 10-14 to highlight the treatment of
Aborigines in Australia.
</P>
</TEXT>
