<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Walker Might Stay on DL  </HEADLINE>
By AARON J. LOPEZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- With season-ending elbow surgery looking more
likely, Larry Walker has hired a personal trainer and a
nutritionist in an attempt to end his annual injury woes.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, on the disabled list since Aug. 21, hoped to return to
Colorado's lineup this week but complained of pain in his right
elbow after taking batting practice and playing catch Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Although no decision had been made, arthroscopic surgery
probably will be required to remove a bone spur from Walker's
elbow, which has plagued him throughout the season.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's been discussed,'' Walker said Monday. ''I think it
might happen. I don't know when, if it's now or at the end of the
season. I'm still in the dark on everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockies manager Buddy Bell said there was a 50 percent chance
Walker would not play again this season. A final decision was
expected within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ''Other than we would like to have him back to help us with the
rest of the season, there is no reason,'' Bell said when asked what
would be gained by Walker's return.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, the two-time defending NL batting champion, was hitting
.309 with nine homers and 51 RBIs in 87 games before going on the
disabled list for the second time this year. He has played in 140
games twice in 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to shake the injury bug, Walker said he plans to
start a three-month workout program with a professional trainer on
Nov. 1, and a nutritionist will regulate his diet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something I wish I could shake,'' he said. ''I'm trying
to take all the right steps to avoid this.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker was placed on the disabled list two weeks ago with
instructions not to pick up a ball or a bat.
</P>
<P>
   The rest appeared to help alleviate the onset of a stress
fracture, but a bone spur has developed, and there is loose
material in Walker's elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our doctors have termed this as gravel or small loose bodies
in the elbow,'' Rockies trainer Tom Probst said. ''If it was just
that, we probably wouldn't consider surgery, but because there also
is a spur on the end of the elbow, we have to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker said he is prepared to do whatever the Rockies want --
within reason. Don't expect to see him playing winter ball after
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I'm playing winter ball at 34 years old, there's a
problem,'' he said. ''I want to win a world series, but I don't
want to win a Caribbean World Series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
