<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Web-based services aim to improve patients' health, cut doctors' costs </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Two years after having quadruple bypass
surgery, Bruce Krawitz still gets so caught up in his business,
Antique Style Lighting, that he occasionally forgets to take his
heart medication.
</P>
<P>
   So the 50-year-old Nyack, N.Y., man reluctantly let his wife
sign him up for a new service that calls, beeps or e-mails patients
repeatedly each day until they confirm via the keypad that they
have taken their medicine.
</P>
<P>
   For a couple days, the automated calls, in the voice of his
doctor's secretary, were ''annoying, horrible'' - until he ignored
them for so many hours he suffered severe chest pain.
</P>
<P>
   ''After that experience, every time I hear that voice, I stop
what I'm doing and I take the medicine,'' Krawitz said last week.
''Four weeks, and I'm trained like a dog already.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the intent of the Internet company providing the
service, Livingston-based PanHealth, or ''total health.'' The
company, founded primarily by physicians on a $2 million
investment, offers a wide range of Web-based services aimed at
keeping patients healthier while helping their doctors cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea is to motivate people to be healthier,'' said Avi
Kulkarni, chairman and chief executive officer of the 10-month-old
company.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Tirch, a 55-year-old disabled Ridgewood man who takes 10
medicines each day for diabetes and severe complications, is among
those using the medication reminder service.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a constant reminder of how sick I am,'' and the need to
follow doctors' orders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company is signing up doctors to have their
patients receive computerized reminders they have an appointment
coming up or need a flu shot, or to set up secure electronic
archives of patients files on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Patients could access part of those files to enter information
about allergies, treatment by other doctors and nonprescription
medicines they take. In addition, using PanHealth's Web server
eliminates the need for doctors to constantly upgrade their own
computer equipment, saving money and time for staff training.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eventually, with electronic record retrieval, we should save
money,'' said Dr. Kenneth A. Black, medical director of a new
PanHealth client, a family doctors' practice called Porter Health
Services in Portage, Ind. ''We don't have a flu shot recall system,
so that could generate more revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting next month, doctors for whom PanHealth created
''virtual offices'' on the Web will be able to post their office
calendar to let patients pick an appointment time, and doctors who
use a handheld computer will be able to e-mail prescriptions to a
pharmacy and be notified whether the patient fills the
prescription. That can be crucial information, as many
prescriptions written for chronic illnesses are never filled.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they take their medicine regularly, they will be healthier
and have less complications,'' said Dr. Bhupen Kapadia, a surgeon
at Christ Hospital in Jersey City and vice chairman of PanHealth's
board.
</P>
<P>
   When patients, especially those with chronic diseases, don't
take medication or follow doctor's orders all the time, serious
complications can land them in the hospital - or worse. Diabetics
who don't control their blood sugar, for example, can go blind or
have to have a limb amputated because of poor circulation, while
people with unchecked high blood pressure can suffer a heart attack
or stroke.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, the annual cost of patient noncompliance, for
additional medical care and lost productivity, is estimated at more
than $100 billion, roughly one-tenth of all health-care spending.
</P>
<P>
   Most of PanHealth's services are offered to patients and doctors
for free or at a minimal cost, while the company tries to sell ads
on its Web site and doctors on its moneymaking services.
</P>
<P>
   Those include training physicians' office staff on the
''e-health'' business and offering doctors overnight, discounted
transcription of their notes from patient exams.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors can download the information by dictating over the phone
after each appointment or by using two types of electronic devices.
The data is shipped via the Internet to India, where clerks type it
into a computer and a physician edits the information before
e-mailing it back in one of several formats.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this company has a good plan,'' said Dr. Vimal Pathak,
a general and oncology surgeon in Valparaiso, Ind., who says he has
been saving nearly 50 percent over his old transcription service.
</P>
<P>
   Pathak plans to gradually convert all his paper patient files to
electronic ones.
</P>
<P>
   ''I might go into the whole virtual office thing,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   PanHealth's next big project is refining its prototype ''Smart
Pill Box,'' an electronic device wire to the telephone that alerts
patients, and eventually their relatives and doctors, if they don't
open the box on time to take their medication.
</P>
<P>
   PanHealth also is working on creating various partnerships with
insurers, government agencies, drug companies, hospitals and
doctors' practices - any groups that could benefit from patients
taking their medicine and staying healthier, or from sales of the
new technology involved.
</P>
<P>
   Computer maker Hewlett-Packard Co., for example, is working on a
deal to refine its handheld PCs to better enable PanHealth clients
to transmit and receive patient information anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see some very good things'' from the partnership developing,
said Richard Williams, an H-P sales specialist in Paramus.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.PanHealth.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-04-00 1842 </TRAILER>
