<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson Back After Leg Injury  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- A little frustrated and plenty banged
up, Rob Johnson was back on his feet Monday, saying the feeling and
movement has returned to his lower left leg.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can control the movement. It's a lot better. It's just real
weak right now and I'm sure in the next couple of days it'll come
back,'' the Buffalo Bills quarterback said, adding he expects to
practice on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After being sacked five times and taking numerous other vicious
licks, Johnson went down with what he called a ''stinger'' just
above his left ankle five minutes into the fourth quarter of the
Bills' 16-13 victory over Tennessee on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being praised for his perseverance in the face of an
imposing pass rush, Johnson was discouraged that he was forced to
once again leave a game he started.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just frustrated that I left the field,'' he said. ''You
get tired of being carried off the field, or limping off the field,
especially in the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   In 10 career starts in Buffalo, Johnson has now been knocked out
of the game five times -- three due to concussions and another due
to a rib injury.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wish I would have stayed in there and finished the game,''
he said. ''It's not like one of those Pyrrhic victories where you
win the battle but lose the war. We won the game, which was nice.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes it a lot easier to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson went down with the Bills ahead 13-6. He said someone
kicked him on the back of the leg, although replays showed that
Johnson's ankle seemed to give out while dropping back.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans scored to tie the game at 13 on their next
possession, but the Bills won when backup Alex Van Pelt sparked the
game-winning drive setting up Steve Christie's 33-yard field goal
with 35 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson still had a solid performance, going 9-of-18 for 107
yards, while also leading the team with 60 yards rushing.
</P>
<P>
   Van Pelt was impressed by Johnson's performance, comparing it to
that to former Bills great Jim Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw Jim Kelly standing there and take hits, Rob took some of
those hits last night. There's no question about his toughness,''
said Van Pelt, in his sixth year with the Bills after being
re-signed last month when Doug Flutie tore a groin muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll take the save but (Johnson) definitely deserves the win,
there's no question. He did all the hard work,'' he said. ''To keep
competing, a lot of guys may have folded in that situation. He
stood up. They kept coming at him, and he kept taking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Wade Phillips said Johnson's performance inspired the
entire team.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody after the game, all our players, were talking about
Rob's toughness,'' Phillips said. ''I thought Rob showed
exceptional toughness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
