<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish Premier: Long Road to Peace  </HEADLINE>
By CIARAN GILES
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Responding to an upsurge in separatist
violence, Spain's prime minister on Monday vowed he would grant no
leeway for the gunmen and predicted a long battle for peace in the
Basque region.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a long road,'' Prime Minister Jose Maria
Aznar Aznar said in an interview with The Associated Press. ''We're
faced with terrorism, pure and simple. And in the European Union
and modern democracies of this century there can be no room for
terror.''
</P>
<P>
   Aznar spoke upon returning to his Moncloa Palace residence in
Madrid after nearly a month in his seaside residence in eastern
Spain -- a holiday interrupted by funerals for five of the eight
people killed this summer in car bombs and shootings blamed on the
armed Basque separatist group ETA.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent victim was Manuel Indiano, a small town
councilor for Aznar's Popular Party gunned down Wednesday in his
candy shop. The death brought to 10 the number of Popular Party
councilors whose deaths are blamed on ETA.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had better Augusts,'' he said bitterly. ''I hope to have
better ones in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiano's death was the 12th since ETA ended a 14-month
unilateral cease-fire in December and unleashed one of its most
brutal offensives ever in what many see as a desperate attempt to
force the government into negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ETA, a Basque-language acronym for Basque Homeland and Freedom,
demands the right to self determination for Spain's three Basque
provinces in the north. It envisions an independent state that
would also incorporate Basque regions in southwestern France.
</P>
<P>
   ETA was particularly active toward the end of the dictatorship
of Gen. Francisco Franco and the first few years of Spain's
transition to democracy following his death in 1975. The violence
subsided slightly under the socialist government that ended in 1996
with Aznar's first election as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the Basques have maintained a separate cultural
identity and language. For some, ETA's fight is a legitimate battle
for sovereignty. But the majority of Spaniards oppose their goals,
pointing out that under Spain's democratic constitution, the
Basques enjoy more autonomy than any other region in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''Terrorism is just another expression of tyranny....They are
Nazis those people who support terrorism in the Basque Country,''
Aznar said.
</P>
<P>
   During the cease-fire, ETA's longest in its 32-year-campaign, a
single round of negotiations failed to get either side to budge.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar, a survivor of an ETA car bomb in 1995, said prospects for
peace, or even negotiations, in the near future are slim.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will never accept Spanish democracy or liberties in Spain
being sacrificed on the altar of some negotiations that might prove
justification for the terrorists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The violence brought an end to any political honeymoon for Aznar
after winning a second term in office with a landslide victory in
the March elections. At the time he was hailed at home and abroad
as representing a new and dynamic Spain whose centrist policies
were fueling a thriving economy.
</P>
<P>
   Aznar rules out any fresh initiatives and insists the government
will persist in maintaining law and order, boosting police
efficiency and seeking greater international cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 1853 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000904.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McNown Runs More Than Enis  </HEADLINE>
By RICK GANO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- Who got the most carries and the most
yards for the Chicago Bears on Sunday? Not promising tailback James
Allen, who's getting a bigger role in the offense. Not the burly
Curtis Enis, who appears to have a diminished role.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears' leading rusher after one game is quarterback Cade
McNown, who took off running 10 times in a season-opening loss to
the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   McNown's tally of 87 yards rushing was the most by a Chicago
quarterback in 27 years, since another left-hander, Bobby Douglass,
gained 100 yards on 19 carries against Green Bay in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   But, that was a different era. Douglass, in fact, is the
10th-leading rusher in Bears history and gained 968 yards in 1972
when he led the team.
</P>
<P>
   So will McNown, who was sore Monday, be taking off from the
pocket so frequently this week when the Bears play at Tampa Bay?
</P>
<P>
   ''You'll see it. It's the nature of his game, nature of our
game,'' coach Dick Jauron said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of them are designed runs, and a number of his scrambles
aren't designed. It will always be part of our game plan. It's a
weapon that's hard to defend against.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears found that out firsthand Sunday when Vikings
quarterback Duante Culpepper, who stands 6-foot-4 and weighs 266
pounds, scored on three touchdown runs in his first NFL start. He
had 13 carries for 73 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just very difficult to defend a quarterback that can
maneuver on the field and beat you with his arms or his legs,''
Jauron said.
</P>
<P>
   The inability to contain Culpepper on his short-yard TD runs,
big second-half plays by Randy Moss and Robert Smith after Chicago
had contained them much of the game, and a fourth-quarter
unnecessary roughness penalty on offensive tackle Blake
Brockermeyer, led to the Bears' undoing in the 30-27 loss at the
Metrdome. Chicago led 20-9 in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Brockermeyer was whistled when he shoved Minnesota's Talance
Sawyer, just seconds after Sawyer made a late hit on McNown
following a 14-yard completion to Alonzo Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   The pass and the penalty would have put the Bears at the Vikings
21 and at least in field goal position, trailing 23-20. But
Brockermeyer's penalty wiped out the play, and the ball went back
to the 50.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a brutal hit on the quarterback in the open field where
the quarterback was lying on the ground,'' Jauron said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And Brock thought Cade was hurt badly and he lost control.
Does that make it right? No. We had 30 yards of offense wiped out
because he lost control, and it's something we don't want to have
happen and unfortunately it did. On the other hand, you can
understand what he sees and feels at the time,'' Jauron added.
</P>
<P>
   McNown, who was 27-of-41 for 290 yards and two touchdowns, used
the quarterback draw to keep the Vikings' pass rush honest, and
also ran for a score.
</P>
<P>
   He had one more carry than Allen, who gained 60 yards, and six
more than Enis, who managed just 11.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's stepped-up role led to the question of whether he is
replacing Enis as the Bears' primary ball carrier?
</P>
<P>
   Enis carried 27 times last year when the Bears beat the Vikings
at the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ''James was running the ball great, and he stayed in there. He
had a great game,'' Enis said Monday, seemingly unconcerned. ''They
didn't want to break up what he was going. That's just the way it
worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Jauron said both backs will continue to play every game.
</P>
<P>
   ''I liked the way they both handled it and the way they
performed,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 1854 </TRAILER>
