<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Officials Fear Train Woes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Olympic organizers have done such a
good job of warning people about traffic problems that they fear
commuters will overload a fragile train system.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are concerned that workers will change their traveling
habits too radically, putting too much pressure on trains that have
been hampered by recent problems.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Willoughby, a spokesman for the Olympic Roads and Transport
Authority, said Olympic crowds will cause the number of passenger
trips on the CityRail network to increase from the normal level of
14 million to about 34 million during the 19-day peak Olympic
period.
</P>
<P>
   And if commuters who have abandoned their cars are added to that
total, the train system could be overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The system can't afford for this to be artificially inflated
by people changing from car to train,'' Willoughby said Monday.
''Put simply, if everyone tries to travel at the same time,
passenger loads will exceed train capacity and very long delays
will be inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Willoughby said that even though on-street parking will not be
allowed in downtown Sydney, commercial garages will be open and
cars will not be banned from the central business district.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also are recommending that commuters travel before 7
a.m. or after 9:30 a.m. during the Olympic period, and that
sightseers begin their trips after 9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there were some problems reported on Olympic shuttle
buses at the main press center and the athletes' village. Officials
said the system is experiencing ''teething problems'' and will be
fixed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 1908 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000904.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jets on Even Keel After Win  </HEADLINE>
By BILL BARNARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- There were no more tears in the New York
Jets locker room on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With a victory at Green Bay behind them and another emotional
game against New England and former Jets defensive coach Bill
Belichick coming up next week, they needed a day to refocus
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''We beat a team in the Packers that historically has a great
record at home and a quarterback in Brett Favre who has a great
reputation for coming back,'' said quarterback Vinny Testaverde,
who broke down crying on the field and in the locker room after
Sunday's 20-16 victory. ''I was very happy and excited, and it just
hit me all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde struggled in the first half, going just 11-of-25 and
throwing an interception, but he finished 23-of-44 for 261 yards
and was brilliant on the game-winning touchdown drive in the fourth
quarter. A 3-yard TD pass to Curtis Martin was set up by a
61-yarder to Dedric Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde said several factors -- his return from last year's
season-ending Achilles' tendon injury, the death of his father in
February 1999 and the exciting finish -- combined to bring out his
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ''Getting the win, feeling the presence of my father, wishing he
was here, all those things made it emotional and made it special,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Al Groh, who won his head coaching debut after a long career as
an assistant, shrugged off Testaverde's emotional display by saying
''Hey, he's Italian.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole team had a resolve to win, and nobody has to project
that resolve more than the quarterback,'' Groh said. ''Each quarter
was progressively better for him. It projects to the rest of the
team. His passes to Ward and Martin were bulls-eye throws where he
had just a little lane to throw through.''
</P>
<P>
   Jets cornerback Aaron Glenn said going to Green Bay and winning
''was a boost to our confidence. The Packers are going to win a lot
of games, especially in their ballpark. Now we have to get ready
for Bill (Belichick). He knows us, and he will try to exploit
that.''
</P>
<P>
   After Martin's TD catch, the Jets had to hold off a final drive
by Favre and the Packers, who reached the New York 35 with 1:08
left. But an interception by Jets safety Victor Green ended the
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've earned the right to look at themselves a little
differently,'' Groh said. ''They went into a tough place and won,
and it should give them reinforcement that they've done something
good when the game went down to the wire. You'd like to have a lot
of 34-7 games, but the reality is that you won't get a lot of
those.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing for us to do is follow up on what we did because
they all count as just one (win).''
</P>
<P>
   Left tackle Jason Fabini, considered one of the best offensive
linemen on the team, was benched by Groh in the fourth quarter
after committing four penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a running back gets 120 yards and fumbles twice, was that a
good day?'' Groh asked. ''The bad plays cancel out the good ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Groh indicated it was likely Fabini would start against the
Patriots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
