<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chargers Misfire On Game Plan  </HEADLINE>
By BERNIE WILSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The way the San Diego Chargers played in their
opener, it might as well still be 1999 -- or even 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The defense played a great game and the offense let it get away,
losing 9-6 at Oakland on Sunday in a game marked by the return of
quarterback Ryan Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Leaf commit his fourth turnover of the game with an
interception on a questionable play selection by the coaches on
fourth-and-inches with 1:25 to play, but it turned out the Chargers
misfired on their game plan overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers expected the Raiders to blitz Leaf into oblivion.
They didn't, although Leaf still was hit several times, including
once on a late hit by Regan Upshaw that left Leaf bloodied and
needing stitches in his chin. The Chargers didn't adjust, and found
themselves in matchups they couldn't handle.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers didn't expect the Oakland crowd to be as vocal as
it was, which contributed to some of the mistakes by Leaf, who
missed last year with a shoulder injury and was playing in his
first real game in nearly 21 months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think of how well that defense played yesterday, eight
three-and-outs they gave us, and we can't let that go to waste,''
Leaf said. ''That's a championship defense is what we have, so we
have to develop that championship offense. Believe me, I'm going to
get better. This offense is going to get better and we're going to
win some ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf said the Chargers had a great game plan, but he also seemed
to diplomatically question the way it was executed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't really get to run a lot of our game plan,'' Leaf
said. ''They were trying to protect me. They've just got to let me
do what I can do. You know, put those five wideouts out there and
let's play football. Know that, hey, I know what's happening around
me now and let's go forward with that. And they know that. I don't
think we were as aggressive as we should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf said the Chargers used eight-man protections a lot on third
down, while the Raiders dropped into a seven-man zone to cover two
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were a lot of black shirts back there and only two white
ones,'' Leaf said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the coaches wanting to protect him from the blitz ''was
a good thought process, but you've got to be able to see that
during the game and make the adjustments and go forward with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they were more worried about bringing a lot of people
at me and me not seeing it, but I see what's going on out there.
I'm very comfortable in what we want to do. I've just got to drive
the car,'' Leaf said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it looked more like a car wreck. Leaf didn't throw a
touchdown pass, was intercepted three times and fumbled twice,
losing one. The only two TD passes he's thrown came during his
awful rookie season of 1998, when he committed 19 turnovers. He now
has 23 career turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Said coach Mike Riley: ''I didn't intend that we would be
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf didn't really have an explanation for the turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think the game yesterday was dictated because it was
my 10th start,'' he said. ''I was very comfortable sitting back
there throwing. Even after getting hit that one time, I didn't have
jittery feet or anything. I don't foresee it continuing.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaf said Sunday that he thought he might have broken his left
hand, but X-rays were negative.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
