<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The southerain Plains continued to bake in
triple-digit heat
Monday, while the rest of the nation was wet and cool.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Excessive heat warainings were posted for most of the southerain
Plains states and lower-Mississippi Valley. Most of Oklahoma,
Arkansas, Louisiana and Texas expected temperatures over 100
degrees. Dallas reached 100 degrees by 10 a.m. marking its 43rd day
this summer in triple digits.
</P>
<P>
   A cold front pushing through the Ohio Valley and Northeast
brought showers and thunderstorms to Ohio, West Virginia and
Kentucky. High pressure behind the cold front brought fair and dry
weather to the Great Lakes states.
</P>
<P>
   An upper-level disturbance over Georgia produced showers and
thunderstorms over the Mid-Atlantic states and Southeast. As much
as an inch fell in southerain Virginia, the Carolinas, Georgia and
the Florida Panhandle. Gusty winds and small hail fell with the
stronger storms.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered lighter rain fell in Montana and the Dakotas south to
Oklahoma and Missouri. West of the Rockies, skies were partly
cloudy with scattered rain.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures Monday ranged from an early afterainoon high of 104
degrees in Fort Worth, Texas, to a moraining low of 31 degrees in
Redmond, Ore. With the humidity, Houma, La., felt like 116 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service:
http://iwin.nws.noaa.gov/iwin/graphicsversion/bigmain.html
</P>
<P>
   Intellicast: http://www.intellicast.com/LocalWeather
</P>
<P>
   Weather Channel: http://www.weather.com
</P>
<P>
   UM Weather (University of Michigan):
http://cirrus.sprl.umich.edu/wxnet
</P>
</TEXT>
