<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Labor Day parade begins march to Election Day  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH PLAINFIELD, N.J. (AP) - On Labor Day, the candidates got
to work.
</P>
<P>
   Marching simultaneously but separately in this town's elaborate
annual parade, Democrat Jon Corzine and Republican Bob Franks
marked the unofficial start of election season with waves,
handshakes and hugs.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, tan from a weekend of politicking on beaches and
boardwalks, then paid visits to a street fair in Rutherford and a
campaign kickoff picnic for Democrats in Highland Park.
</P>
<P>
   Franks visited Rutherford's street fair. A planned visit to
Closter was canceled by summer rains, but Franks was to continue to
Scotch Plains later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Working the Rutherford street fair from opposite directions,
Franks and Corzine crossed paths amid concession stands and craft
vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ''Haven't been to church in a while, so I haven't seen you,''
Corzine told Franks during a lengthy handshake. The two men live in
adjoining Union County towns and both worship at Christ Church in
Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine and Franks have been running for the U.S. Senate for
nearly a year. But the ceremonial close of summer brings the fall
election season in focus, and with polls showing 20 to 25 percent
of New Jersey voters undecided, Corzine and Franks have some
influencing to do.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, each man had 64 days to assemble a winning
coalition of party faithful and swayed independents.
</P>
<P>
   What's their pitch to voters?
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope they know that I believe we ought to use this
prosperity to invest in the progress of the country - on health
care, education, the environment - and that we ought to be an
inclusive society in all aspects,'' said Corzine, the former
chairman of Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. who is in his first race for public
office.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have said Corzine's proposals for universal health
care, universal long-term care for seniors and universal preschool
would more than soak up the entire federal budget surplus. But
Corzine said, ''I think we can do that fiscally responsibly. Matter
of fact, I know we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks, who hopes to join the Senate after four terms in the
House, didn't criticize his opponent, focusing instead on his own
strengths.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am very much like most of the people who call New Jersey
their home,'' he said. ''I was raised by a great family. They
instilled in me the values that I believe are mainstream in our
state, and I hope people get to know the kind of public official
I've been for the past 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hold a 54-46 majority in the Senate, and Democrats
insist they have a chance to win enough seats to take control. To
do so, they certainly need to win in New Jersey, where Corzine and
Franks are seeking the seat being vacated by Democrat Frank
Lautenberg after 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's Senate campaign is shaping up as a referendum on
Corzine. With an estimated net worth of $400 million, Corzine spent
an unprecedented $36 million - most of it from his own pockets - to
defeat former Gov. Jim Florio in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Florio accused him of buying a Senate seat. Franks has leveled a
similar charge.
</P>
<P>
   The Corzine campaign began airing two ads in Philadelphia and
New York television stations that will mark the start of a
nine-week wave of television and radio advertisements until
Election Day, Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine saturated the airways for eight weeks prior to the
primary in June. He said that his general election ad campaign will
not be as massive because he is now better known.
</P>
<P>
   While assailing Corzine's spending, Franks has been trying hard
to narrow the financial chasm. As Corzine met voters up and down
the Jersey coast this weekend, Franks spent Saturday and Sunday in
private meetings and on the phone, trying to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-year-old girl watching the Monday parade, Shakera Jones of
South Plainfield, was in satisfactory condition after she was run
over by a float Monday morning. She was flown to Robert Wood
Johnson University Hospital in New Brunswick after the accident,
which halted the parade for about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   South Plainfield police said the girl ran up to the float to
give a water bottle to someone riding on it, slipped to the ground
between the front and rear axles of the flatbed carrying it, and
the rear tires ran over her, causing severe leg injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Tomei, 42, of South Plainfield, who drove the truck pulling
the float, suffered chest pains and shock immediately afterward and
was taken to Muhlenberg Regional Medical Center. A spokesman for
the hospital said Tomei was in guarded condition after being
admitted to the cardiac care unit for chest pains and hypertension.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-09-04-00 2048 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000904.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman Addresses Taxes, Debates  </HEADLINE>
By BRIGITTE GREENBERG
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- Democratic vice presidential candidate
Joseph Lieberman ended a 27-hour campaign push through five states,
telling union workers Monday that ''no one will work harder for
hard working middle class families'' than he and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to about 400 people at a union hall, Lieberman said
Republican rival George W. Bush's ''monstrous'' tax cut would rule
out possibility of a sustainable prescription drug plan under
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where's he going to get the money?'' asked Lieberman. Bush has
said he would offer details of his prescription drug plan on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also took aim at Bush's debate proposal, saying it was
designed to limit the size of the viewing audience.
</P>
<P>
   Using a football analogy, he told the crowd: ''It's a little bit
like heading toward the Super Bowl and one of the teams says, 'I
don't want to play in that city and I don't like those referees and
I'd only like to play three quarters, and not four, because I don't
want too many people to watch the game this year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has proposed three 60-minute debates, but not under a
format recommended by a bipartisan commission. The Gore campaign
wants three 90-minute debates as recommended by the commission,
saying those will reach the widest audience.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at another labor gathering in Detroit, Lieberman said
he would keep pushing for a place for religion in public life,
telling union workers the ''the labor movement is built on values
that come from faith.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If you see men and women as created in the image of God, then
you will not treat them as extensions of machines, as pure things
to take advantage of, and that is what the labor movement is about,
justice to people, fairness to people,'' Lieberman told about 700
mostly union workers at an annual Labor Day festival Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the Connecticut senator, raised eyebrows last week
when he asserted in a speech here at Fellowship Chapel, one of the
largest black churches in the country, that religious faith should
have a greater role in American public life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I gave kind of a sermon and some people objected to it because
I talked about the place of faith in American life,'' he told the
union rally. ''Some people say, 'Don't say that.' I'm going to keep
saying it because I believe that's what most Americans believe. It
unites us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman pledged that he and Gore would fight for workers'
rights, saying they respect working men and women.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can say that the labor movement was built on values that
come from faith, that were enshrined in the Declaration of
Independence, all of us are created equal. Where did that equality
come from? It was an endowment of our Creator,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman was coming off an all-night campaign run with Gore.
The two campaigned in Philadelphia and Flint, Mich., on Sunday,
arriving in Tampa, Fla., early Monday. From there, Gore headed for
events in Pittsburgh and Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   After Lieberman's Detroit labor rally, he went to Maumee, Ohio,
for a minor league baseball game that pitted the Toledo Mud Hens
against the Columbus Clippers, a farm team of Lieberman's beloved
New York Yankees. The Clippers won 4-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
