<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pinochet Appeals for Chilean Unity  </HEADLINE>
By EDUARDO GALLARDO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- In his first statement since a court
stripped him of his immunity and paved the way for him to stand
trial on human rights charges, Gen. Augusto Pinochet on Monday
called upon Chileans to overcome ''our pains and divisions of the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's brief, conciliatory remarks were read by his
granddaughter, Maria Jose Martinez, at the main entrance to the
former dictator's heavily guarded suburban Santiago residence.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet and his wife, Lucia, stood by their 17-year-old
granddaughter as she read.
</P>
<P>
   ''On this date, I want to express to every man and woman of my
beloved fatherland, that I shelter in my heart the firm hope that
our divisions and pains of the past will be overcome, and we will
set our sight in the future, for the sake of the new generations,''
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet, walking with difficulty and using a cane, returned to
the house holding his wife's arm after their granddaughter read the
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The day marked the so-called ''Day of National Unity,'' a day
that replaced a holiday that had been observed on Sept. 11 -- the
anniversary of the bloody 1973 coup led by Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   Monday also marked the 30th anniversary of the election victory
of Salvador Allende, the Marxist president that Pinochet eventually
toppled in the coup.
</P>
<P>
   Communists and other leftists laid wreaths at the newly
inaugurated monument to Allende, who committed suicide the day of
the coup in his presidential palace under heavy air and ground
military attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being convinced that I have always wanted what is best for my
fatherland, with full humbleness I ask God to give my countrymen
the necessary wisdom to overcome the conflicts of the past and
contribute to a future in peace, unity and progress,'' Pinochet
added.
</P>
<P>
   The ailing, former ruler also made an appeal to preserve the
works of his 17-year old regime, which in spite of massive human
rights violations is widely credited with modernizing Chile and
starting a long period of economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet urged Chileans to work so ''the results achieved with
great effort and sacrifice by all Chileans will not be put at risk,
so it can consolidate and last long.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Pinochet's first public comment since the Supreme Court
last month removed his immunity from prosecution. The action paved
the way for his trial in one of the most notorious cases of rights
abuses during his long reign, the so-called ''caravan of death,''
in which a military squad executed 72 political prisoners shortly
after the coup.
</P>
<P>
   According to an official report, 3,197 people were killed or
''disappeared'' for political reasons under Pinochet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 2051 </TRAILER>
