<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Siamese Twins Need Exam  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- A British appeals court on Monday requested a
second medical opinion before making a life-and-death decision
about the fate of four-week-old Siamese twins.
</P>
<P>
   The three judge panel in the Court of Appeal ordered the second
examination at the start of legal action by the girls' parents to
block a High Court ruling that would mean certain death for one of
their daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Robert Johnson ruled last month that Jodie -- the stronger
of the twins -- should be separated from her sister Mary, who is
reliant on her sister's lungs and heart to survive. If they are
separated, Mary will die, medical experts said. But without the
surgery, both twins are likely to perish within three to six months
because of the extra strain on Jodie's organs. Mary and Jodie are
not the their real names, and the family has not been identified.
</P>
<P>
   The girls were born joined at the lower abdomen on Aug. 8 in
Manchester, northern England. Their parents have opposed an
operation to separate them, saying they did not want one of their
children ''actively killed.'' They have also questioned what kind
of quality of life the surviving twin would have.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Parker, a lawyer assigned to represent the stronger twin,
said medical experts believed that she would not face significant
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must look at it not that something is being done to Mary to
hasten the end of her life, but that something is being done to
Jodie in order to restore to her her own integrity and bodily
system,'' Parker told the court.
</P>
<P>
   A medical team from London's prestigious Great Ormond Street
Hospital agreed to see the twins on Tuesday and report back to the
court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 2114 </TRAILER>
