<HEADLINE> Rams, Broncos Tied After First Q  </HEADLINE>
By R.B. FALLSTROM
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Brian Griese and Az-Zahir Hakim scored
first-quarter touchdowns as the Denver Broncos and St. Louis Rams
were tied 7-7 Monday night in a game matching the last three Super
Bowl champions.
</P>
<P>
   Griese led the Broncos, who won the Super Bowl after the 1997
and '98 seasons but slumped to 6-10 last year, to a touchdown on
their first possession. He scored on an 8-yard bootleg with 10:05
to go as the Broncos drove 59 yards in six plays.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis, who is returning from a serious knee injury,
carried the first three plays for a combined 17 yards, and after
two completions he was an effective decoy on Griese's scoring run.
Griese also hit Rod Smith for 16 yards and Dwayne Carswell for 18
in the drive.
</P>
<P>
   The defending Super Bowl champion Rams blew their first scoring
chance as Al Wilson intercepted a ball that glanced off the hands
of St. Louis tight end Roland Williams at the 7 with 5:22 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' defense held after five plays, and Hakim returned Tom
Rouen's punt 86 yards to tie the score with 2:05 left in the
quarter. Hakim also returned a punt for a touchdown last Oct. 3
against the Cincinnati Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were making their first Monday night appearance since
Nov. 25, 1991, a 33-10 loss to the San Francisco 49ers. St. Louis
hadn't had a Monday night game since 1986.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
