<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, Lieberman Wrap Up All-Nighter  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- A caffeinated Al Gore marched, not danced, to
''The Pennsylvania Polka,'' still standing Monday after an
all-nighter with the graveyard shift and more than 10,000
supporters behind him.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential candidate and running mate Joseph
Lieberman wrapped up the madcap and sleepless 28-hour campaign
sprint as a Labor Day anthem to American workers. As for
presidential politics, this was ''time to turn up the heat,'' said
Gore, sustained by five changes of shirts, two pre-dawn breakfasts
and rotations of coffee and Diet Coke.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats beckoned to middle-class voters with a fired-up
argument against the broad $1.3 trillion tax-cut package at the
heart of Republican George W. Bush's rival campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd veto that in a minute,'' Gore said at the Louisville Motor
Speedway in Kentucky, where he lost count of the hours just as his
marathon reached the finish line. ''I've been at this for 30
straight hours. You're going to get the unvarnished truth -- you
know it!''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as if to inch closer to that 30-hour mark, he made
unscheduled stops at a fire station and to shake hands with Taco
Bell workers.
</P>
<P>
   Believing the race he and Bush began two years ago started fresh
on Labor Day, Gore is using the week to present his agenda for the
economy as shiny and new. He emphasized balanced budgets, paying
off the national debt and using budget surpluses to improve
schools, health care and the environment. He planned an economic
speech Wednesday in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to handle this responsibly. We've shown in the
last eight years that we know how to do that,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Around 6:30 a.m. or Hour 14, as he greeted 500 Florida
enthusiasts at a West Tampa fire station, Gore began to ramble and
repeat himself. But from the back of a firetruck, his populist
us-against-them focus remained sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ''How can we stand by as the rich get richer and the poor get
poorer? ... I'll be durned if we're going to go back to the old
ways of just borrow and spend and go into debt in order to give a
big tax cut to the wealthy,'' he drawled.
</P>
<P>
   Seven hours later, he regaled Pittsburgh supporters with tales
of the strapped senior citizens he'd met who need Medicare coverage
for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed a Medicare drug benefit at a 10-year cost of
about $253 billion. Bush belatedly promised to outline a proposal
on Tuesday. Gore's economic analysts preemptively crunched numbers
to argue there's no room for drug aid in a Bush budget heavy with
tax cuts, unless he were to start digging deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett retorted, ''Why should people be
expected to believe his math calculations of Governor Bush's budget
proposals?''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who split from Gore in Tampa to cover more ground in
Michigan, Ohio and Illinois, told Detroit union workers at a rally,
''This guy is working me!''
</P>
<P>
   With daytime fireworks over the Allegheny River and the nonstop
frenzy, Gore and Lieberman sought to create an image of themselves
in the lead of this race. They zeroed in on tossup states where,
aides said, internal campaign polling over the past two weeks has
been encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you ever wondered whether Michigan is central to what
happens in this election, I've been here three times in the last
week and twice in the last 10 hours,'' Lieberman, who had been with
Gore for a midnight stop in Flint, joked at Detroit's annual Labor
Day festival.
</P>
<P>
   A burst of confetti and a band playing ''The Pennsylvania
Polka'' greeted Gore as he, AFL-CIO President John Sweeney and the
Rev. Jesse Jackson strode from Pittsburgh's Labor Day parade into
Point State Park and a crowd that police put at 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Gore advisers suffered a mix of satisfaction from what Lieberman
called ''adrenaline surge'' and sheer exhaustion. On one leg,
Gore's brother-in-law, Frank Hunger, tried sleeping on the floor of
Air Force Two but couldn't find a spare pillow.
</P>
<P>
   Still, adviser Greg Simon delighted in the contrast to Bush's
holiday weekend itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yesterday's event was one bogus press conference. Today he's
got one talk,'' Simon sniffed. ''He's running a Rose Garden
campaign without a rose garden.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
