<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressEdward Anhalt:
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Academy Award-winning writer Edward Anhalt,
best known for his work on the films ''Becket'' and ''Jeremiah
Johnson,'' died Sunday of cancer. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Anhalt won Academy Awards for 1964's ''Becket'' and 1950's
''Panic in the Streets.'' He was nominated for ''The Sniper'' in
1952, which he co-wrote with Edna Anhalt, the first of his five
wives.
</P>
<P>
   Among his credits are 1957's ''Pride and the Passion'' with Cary
Grant and Sophia Loren, the 1962 Elvis Presley film ''Girls, Girls,
Girls,'' 1968's ''The Boston Strangler'' with Henry Fonda, and
1981's ''Green Ice'' with Ryan O'Neal and Anne Archer.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote the 1972 Robert Redford movie ''Jeremiah Johnson'' with
''Apocalypse Now'' co-writer John Milius.
Lucille Fletcher:
</P>
<P>
   LANGHORNE, Pa. (AP) -- Lucille Fletcher, a writer whose radio
dramas included ''Sorry, Wrong Number'' and ''The Hitchhiker,''
which was performed by Orson Welles, died Aug. 31st. She was 88.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sorry, Wrong Number,'' twice was made into a movie. A 1948
version starred Burt Lancaster and Barbara Stanwyck, who received
an Academy Award nomination for her portrayal of a rich, bedridden
woman who overhears two men planning a murder. A 1989 television
version starred Loni Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Other Fletcher stories were the basis for the 1944 Cary Grant
film ''Once Upon a Time'' and the 1965 Rock Hudson thriller
''Blindfold.'' Her play ''Night Watch'' also made it to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Her radio thriller ''The Hitchhiker'' was performed by Orson
Welles on his CBS show in 1941. Welles' Mercury Theater group also
performed her radio play ''The Search for Henry Le Fevre.'' Other
radio works featured such stars as Vincent Price and Ida Lupino.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher also wrote several novels, including ''The Daughters of
Jasper Clay,'' ''Eighty Dollars to Stamford'' and ''Mirror Image.''
Ralph Looney:
</P>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE (AP) -- Ralph Looney, a former editor at The
Albuquerque Tribune and the Rocky Mountain News in Denver, died
Monday following a lengthy illness. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   Looney, who was editor of The Tribune from 1973 to 1980, joined
The Tribune as a reporter in 1953. He left two years later for a
stint with the St. Louis Globe Democrat, then returned to The
Tribune as city editor in 1956. He was named assistant managing
editor in 1968 and editor in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, he won the prestigious Robert F. Kennedy journalism
award for a nine-part series on the Navajos.
</P>
<P>
   Looney left The Tribune in 1980 to become editor of the Rocky
Mountain News, which he headed until his retirement in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote two books, ''Haunted Highways,'' a collection of
tales about New Mexico ghost towns, published in 1968, and
''O'Keeffe and Me: A Treasured Friendship,'' the story of his
association with New Mexico artist Georgia O'Keeffe, published in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife Clara.
Bess Taffel:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Bess Taffel, a screenwriter whose career
dried up after she was blacklisted for refusing to cooperate with
the House Un-American Activities Committee, died July 21 of a
stroke. She was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Taffel began writing for studios after working with a
progressive Hollywood theater company. Her screen credits included
''Badman's Territory,'' ''A Likely Story'' and ''Elopement.''
</P>
<P>
   In ''Tender Comrades,'' a history of the blacklist period by
Patrick McGilligan and Paul Buhle, Taffel admitted she had joined
the Communist Party and said it was the ''most patriotic thing I'd
ever done in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   After refusing to answer questions before the House committee in
1951, her began to decline.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 2204 </TRAILER>
