<HEADLINE> Cincinnati 23, Army 17  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Deontey Kenner threw a 12-yard touchdown pass
to Jason Collins-Baker with 6:11 left as Cincinnati rallied to beat
Army 23-17 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kenner completed 18 of 29 passes for 239 yards for Cincinnati,
which overcame a 17-13 deficit in season opener to snap a six-game
losing streak in Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   ''Deontey played great as expected,'' Cincinnati coach Rick
Minter said. ''We must continue to use him to the best of his
ability for this team to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Army lost its first game under coach Todd Berry, the former
Illinois State coach who took over after Bob Sutton was fired
following a 3-8 season.
</P>
<P>
   ''For as many good players as Cincinnati has, I thought we
handled that pretty well,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any time you play on national TV, you have a chance to expose
your program to recruits. It was good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathon Ruffin added a 26-yard field goal with 31 seconds left
for Cincinnati. Ruffin also connected from 31 and 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's Ray Jackson had a 37-yard touchdown run in the
third quarter, and finished with 108 yards on 26 carries. DeMarco
McCleskey added 90 yards on 19 carries, and Collins-Baker finished
with six receptions for 86 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Army's Alton McCallum scored on a 1-yard run in the third
quarter, and the Cadets' Chad Jenkins threw an 8-yard touchdown
pass to Michael Wallace early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins was 14-of-29 for 123 yards with an interception. Wallace
ran for 56 yards on 14 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati gained 437 yards in total offense and held Army to
243 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''They stepped it up and got the job done,'' Kenner said of the
Bearcats' defense. ''This is a great win for us. Any win,
especially in the conference, is huge. But now that we got this one
off our back, we'll shift our focus to the next game, Syracuse.''
</P>
