<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Leave Volcanic Island  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Only officials and relief workers remained on a
volcanic island south of Tokyo on Monday after stragglers boarded a
boat to flee eruptions and earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   Miyake Island's 400 remaining residents left by ferry in the
afternoon, bound for Tokyo shelters where hundreds of other
islanders have huddled in a three-day evacuation, local official
Yoshiko Numata said.
</P>
<P>
   The order to leave came after 2,686-foot Mount Oyama erupted
Wednesday for the eighth time since early July. Only police, fire
and municipal personnel remained on the island, about 120 miles
south of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday afternoon, nearly 600 people left Miyake by ferry.
More than 60 percent of the island's population of 3,855 had
already fled to the mainland before Friday's evacuation order.
</P>
<P>
   The eruptions have blanketed the island, part of the Izu chain,
with ash, prompting warnings that heavy rain could set off
mudslides. It has also been shaken by thousands of earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   The government set up shelters in Tokyo, which administers
Miyake, and dispatched ships to the island. Troops requested by
Tokyo Gov. Shintaro Ishihara have cleared ash from roads and
rooftops.
</P>
<P>
   Experts have said shifts in huge underground pools of magma are
responsible for the recent volcanic and seismic activity on Miyake.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, a volcano on Japan's northern main island of
Hokkaido erupted for the first time in nearly two years, spewing
ash and white smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Komagatake, a 3,716-foot mountain, erupted late Monday
night, the Sapporo District Meteorological Observatory said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the eruption, a small amount of ash was observed on
the ground in a town located northwest of the mountain, the
observatory said. The mountain's last eruption, on Oct. 25, 1998,
was minor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
