<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami To Expatriates: Help Iran  </HEADLINE>
By KARINE G. BARZEGAR
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami on
Monday urged hundreds of Iranian expatriates living in the United
States to embrace their native land and unite to forge a better
future for Iran.
</P>
<P>
   With signs of a thaw in U.S.-Iranian relations, Khatami stressed
the importance of dialogue and interaction among all Iranians, and
asked those inside and outside the country to use their energy to
help Iran develop economically.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our hearts are beating for the love of one place, and this
place is Iran,'' Khatami said, as the audience that filled a U.N.
conference room applauded.
</P>
<P>
   The reformist president did not mention a bill submitted to the
Iranian parliament Sunday that would grant amnesty to Iranians who
fled the country because of anti-government activities or ties to
outlawed political parties. But his speech clearly signaled his
support for an open door for expatriates.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing concern about an Iranian brain drain, the president
said he hopes Iranians across the world will pool their knowledge
and scientific skills to create a new advanced civilization.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today, we cannot go forward without good technology, science
and management,'' he said. ''The brilliant generation of Iranians
that lives inside and outside the country can help us, since they
happen to be our new investment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Iranian-American response was largely positive,
many businessmen at the event said they needed to have the approval
of all powers -- including the country's hard-line supreme leader,
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei -- in order to start investing in economic
projects in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami is in New York to attend the U.N. Millennium Summit of
more than 150 world leaders, making only his second visit to the
United Nations since his 1997 election. The gathering is being held
just before Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez hosts a summit of the
oil cartel in late September.
</P>
<P>
   The Iranian president said he had no sympathy for demands that
oil prices should be lowered.
</P>
<P>
   Although Khatami addressed Iranian-Americans at a similar U.N.
meeting in 1998, it was believed to be the first time that members
of the Jewish-Iranian community and other religious minorities --
such as Armenians and Zoroastrians -- were invited to listen to the
president in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Khatami, wearing the flowing black robe and turban of a senior
Shiite cleric, paid tribute to the role of religious minorities in
Iran's history.
</P>
<P>
   ''I though his speech was wonderful since he stressed the fact
that we are all Iranians and all equal,'' said Banouh Mehr, a
Zoroastrian-Iranian in her mid-fifties.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mehr, many Iranian-Americans at the meeting viewed
Khatami's speech as an attempt to reassure religious minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he wanted to give the assurance that any matter
involving those communities will be conducted fairly,'' said Trita
Parsi, head of Iranians for International Cooperation, a grassroots
organization working to end U.S. sanctions and promote U.S.-Iranian
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is about dialogue between the Iranian community and the
government: the dialogue among civilizations needs to start at
home,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-09-04-00 2245 </TRAILER>
