<HEADLINE> Rams Lead Broncos 21-17 at Half  </HEADLINE>
By R.B. FALLSTROM
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Kurt Warner hit Ricky Proehl for a 6-yard score
with 38 seconds to go in the first half as the St. Louis Rams took
a 21-17 lead over the Denver Broncos on Monday night in a matchup
of the last three Super Bowl champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams, who beat the Tennessee Titans 23-16 in the Super Bowl
last January, drove 77 yards in nine plays to take the lead.
Warner, the NFL MVP who threw 41 touchdown passes last year in his
first season as starter, was 15-of-20 for 173 yards in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Denver, which won the Super Bowl after the 1997 and '98 seasons
but faltered to a 6-10 record last year, had taken the lead on a
25-yard pass from Brian Griese to Rod Smith with 3:50 left in the
half.
</P>
<P>
   A 47-yard pass from Griese to Smith set up the Broncos' other
second-quarter score, a 32-yard field goal by Jason Elam that put
Denver ahead 10-7.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Faulk scored his 50th career rushing touchdown on a
5-yard run to put the Rams ahead 14-10 with 8:53 to go in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos played the second quarter without Terrell Davis, who
twisted his left ankle. Davis, who missed the last 12 games with a
serious knee injury last year, had 34 yards on nine carries.
</P>
<P>
   Griese, who was 7-of-11 for 133 yards in the half, led the
Broncos to a touchdown on their first possession. He scored on an
8-yard bootleg with 10:05 to go as the Broncos drove 59 yards in
six plays.
</P>
<P>
   Davis carried the first three plays for a combined 17 yards, and
after two completions he was an effective decoy on Griese's scoring
run. Griese also hit Smith for 16 yards and Dwayne Carswell for 18
in the drive.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams blew their first scoring chance as Al Wilson
intercepted a ball that glanced off the hands of St. Louis tight
end Roland Williams at the 7 with 5:22 left.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams' defense held after five plays, and Az-Zahir Hakim
returned Tom Rouen's punt 86 yards to tie the score with 2:05 left
in the first quarter. Hakim also returned a punt for a touchdown
last Oct. 3 against the Cincinnati Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   The Rams were making their first Monday night appearance since
Nov. 25, 1991, a 33-10 loss to the San Francisco 49ers. St. Louis
hadn't had a Monday night game since 1986.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
