<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-04 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Soviet leader says post-Cold War thinking is inadequate  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD PYLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev said
Monday that a ''lack of new thinking and political leadership'' was
costing the world community a chance to improve itself in the
aftermath of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   He said globalization - the extending of economic and cultural
opportunities to all people - ''could have many negative
consequences'' if allowed to take place in a spontaneous,
uncontrolled manner. ''It should be governed and guided,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev addressed a dinner audience of several hundred at the
opening of the State of the World Forum 2000, a non-profit
organization whose fifth annual meeting in New York coincides with
the United Nations Millennium Summit, expected to draw leaders from
150 nations.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates said the trend toward globalization already affects
most of Earth's 6 billion people and is accelerating, but in widely
differing and unequal ways that deprive developing nations of the
benefits enjoyed by wealthier nations.
</P>
<P>
   To rectify this, Gorbachev proposed creation of a permanent
''people's assembly'' to focus attention on the issue full time
rather than piecemeal, suggesting it be called the World Citizens
Network for Security and Development.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Noor of Jordan also spoke at the dinner, which opened a
week-long meeting of the World Forum.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev, who was president of the Soviet Union from 1985 until
it collapsed in 1991 and now runs the Gorbachev Foundation, a
Paris-based think tank on international affairs, said the post-Cold
War era is filled with questions about the course of civilization.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where are we succeeding and where are we failing? Everyone is
asking, 'what is happening to all of us?''' he said. ''We do not
fully understand what is emerging. We are living in a new, global
world in which the paradigm of our world is changing ... we are
lacking the political leadership that we need to meet these
challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   He said ''intellectual diversity ... and open-minded debate''
are necessary, because ''statesmen alone cannot solve the task.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev, who spoke Russian with simultaneous interpretation
into English, said the end of the Cold War presented a ''great
opportunity'' that has been wasted by new kinds of international
strife and hard-line policies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mildest I can say is that we have not used well these
opportunities, we have frittered them away,'' he said. ''We have
new conflicts on top of the old conflicts, and we still see
attempts to solve problems by domination and dicta.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited Kosovo as one example.
</P>
<P>
   ''The process of disarmament has slowed down, and there is a
danger of a new arms race,'' he said. ''The G-7 countries and the
transnationals continue to act in the old ways, without realizing
the changes and impulses coming from the world for a civil
society.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said there were some positive signs, mentioning the
European summit and President Clinton's recent decision to defer
any further work on a ballistic missile defense system, adding that
''at the U.N., they recognize that this is a problem that affects
all nations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
